# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-kerensky
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-kerensky/1912-russian-legislative-election] Legislative elections were held in the Russian Empire in September 1912 to elect the 442 members of the fourth State Duma.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1912-russian-legislative-election] The elections to the fourth State Duma were conducted on Electoral Law 1907, which were the same laws as the third State Duma had been elected under in the October 1907 Russian legislative election.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1912-russian-legislative-election] Around 51% of those elected were nobles, the highest during the Tsarist era.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1912-russian-legislative-election] Both the right- and left-wing increased their representation in the Duma; right-wing candidates won 153 seats and left-wingers 152, whilst the centrists, including the Union of October 17, were reduced to 130 seats.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1912-russian-legislative-election] Following the elections, the Union of October 17 became an opposition party due to its harassment by the government during the election.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Elections to the Russian Constituent Assembly were held on 25 November 1917.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Organized as a result of events in the February Revolution, the elections took place two months after they had been originally meant to occur.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] They are generally recognised as the first free elections in Russian history, though they did not produce a democratically elected government, as the Bolsheviks subsequently disbanded the Constituent Assembly and proceeded to rule the country as a one-party state with all opposition parties banned.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Various academic studies have given alternative results.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] However, all indicate that the Bolsheviks were clear winners in the urban centres, and also took around two-thirds of the votes of soldiers on the Western Front.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Nevertheless, the Socialist-Revolutionary party topped the polls, winning a plurality of seats (no party won a majority) on the strength of support from the country's rural peasantry, who were for the most part one-issue voters, that issue being land reform.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Some modern Marxist theoreticians have contested the view that a one-party state was a natural outgrowth of the Bolsheviks' actions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] George Novack stressed the initial efforts by the Bolsheviks to form a government with the Left Socialist Revolutionaries and bring other parties such as the Mensheviks into political legality.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Tony Cliff argued the Bolshevik-Left Socialist Revolutionary coalition government dissolved the Constituent Assembly due to a number of reasons.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] They cited outdated voter-rolls that did not acknowledge the split within the Socialist Revolutionary Party and the assembly's conflict with the elected Russian Congress of the Soviets as an alternative, democratic structure.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The dissolution of the Constituent Assembly was also initially approved by the Left Socialist Revolutionaries and anarchists; both groups were in favour of a more extensive democracy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The convocation of a Constituent Assembly had been a long-standing demand of the democratic and popular movements in Tsarist Russia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In the later phase of the February Revolution, Tsar Nicholas II abdicated on March 2, 1917.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Russian Provisional Government was formed and pledged to carry through with holding elections for a Constituent Assembly.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Consensus emerged between all major political parties to go ahead with the election.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Nevertheless, the various political parties were divided over many details on the organization of the impending election.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Bolsheviks demanded immediate elections, whilst the Socialist-Revolutionaries wanted to postpone the vote for several months for it not to collide with the harvest season.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Right-wing forces also pushed for delay of the election.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] On March 19, 1917 a mass rally was held in Petrograd, demanding female suffrage.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The march gathered some 40,000 participants.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The protest was led by Vera Figner and Poliksena Shishkina-Iavein.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] It moved from the Petrograd City Duma to the Tauride Palace, and the demonstrators refused to vacate the palace grounds before the Provisional Government and the Soviet committed to female suffrage.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] On July 20, 1917, the Provisional Government issued a decree awarding voting rights for women aged 20 years and above.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In May the political parties agreed on main principles of the election (proportional representation, universal suffrage and secret ballot).
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] A special electoral commission was set up, composed of multiple lawyers and legal experts.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The following month September 17, 1917 was set as the election date.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The new Constituent Assembly was supposed to have its first meeting on September 30, 1917.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In July the left-wing parties increased their pressure on the Provisional Government, reaching a nearly insurrectionist situation.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In the end, the following month the left consented to a further postponement.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] On August 9, 1917 a new date for the election was set by the Provisional Government: voting on November 12 and the first session of the Constituent Assembly would be held on November 28, 1917.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Between the finalization of candidate lists and the election, the October Revolution broke out.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The October Revolution ended the reign of the Provisional Government.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] A new Soviet government took charge of the country, the Council of People's Commissars.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Nevertheless, the new government pledged to go ahead with the election and that its rule remained provisional until its authority would be confirmed by the Constituent Assembly.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] 81 electoral districts (*okrugs*) were formed by the Provisional Government.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Electoral districts were generally set up on (pre-revolutionary) governorate or ethnic oblast boundaries.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Moreover, there were electoral districts for the different army groups and fleets.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] There were also an electoral district assigned for the workers at the Chinese Eastern Railroad and one electoral district for the soldiers of the Russian Expeditionary Corps in France and the Balkans (with some 20,000 voters).
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The estimated population of eligible voters at the time (excluding occupied territories) has been estimated at around 85 million; the number of eligible voters in the districts where polling took place has been estimated at around 80 million.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Each party had a separate ballot with a list with names of candidates, there was no general ballot.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The voter would either have received copies of different party lists in advance or at the polling station.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The voter would select one list, place it in an envelope, seal it and place it in the box.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] If any name was scratched, the vote would be invalid.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The voting began on November 12–14, 1917.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The election was at the time the largest election organized in history.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] However, only in 39 districts did the election take place as scheduled.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In many districts the voting occurred in late November or early December, and in some remote places the vote took place only in early January 1918.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In spite of war and turmoil, some 47 million voters exercised their franchise, with a national voter turnout of around 64% (per Protasov (2004)).
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] According to Protasov (2004), the countryside generally had a higher voter turnout than the cities.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] 220 cities across the country, with a combined population of seven million, had a voter turnout of 58%.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In agrarian provinces turnout generally ranged from 62 to 80%.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In Tambov province urban areas had a turnout of 50.2% while rural areas had 74.5%.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] According to Radkey (1989) national voter turnout stood at around 55%.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Socialist-Revolutionaries (SRs) emerged as the most voted party in the election, swaying the broad majority of the peasant vote.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The agrarian programmes of the SR and Bolshevik parties were largely similar, but the peasantry were more familiar with the SRs.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Bolsheviks lacked an organizational presence in many rural areas.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In areas where the Bolshevik electoral campaign had been active (for example, near to towns or garrisons) the peasant vote was somewhat evenly divided between SRs and Bolsheviks.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Moreover, whilst the SRs enjoyed widespread support among the peasantry, the party lacked a strong organizational structure in rural areas.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The party was highly dependent on peasant union, zemstvos, cooperatives and soviets.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] On the issue of war and peace, the SR leadership had vowed not to enter into a separate peace with the Central Powers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The SR leadership condemned the peace talks initiated by the Bolsheviks, but to what extent the SRs were prepared to continue the war was unclear at the time.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Along with the Mensheviks, the SRs supported the notion of engaging with other European socialist politicians to find a settlement to the ongoing World War.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The filing of nominations for the election took place just as the split in the SR party was taking place.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] By late October, when the SR party lists were already set, the Left Socialist-Revolutionaries formed a separate party (PLSR).
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] But whilst by the time of the election the Left SRs had constituted a separate party, the split was not completed in local SR party branches until early 1918.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Kazan, Yaroslavl, Kazan and Kronstadt SR organizations went over to the Left SRs en bloc.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In Ufa and Pskov the majority in the SR party organization crossed over to the Left SRs.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In Petrograd the leftist faction had dominated the SR party branch prior to the October Revolution, but elsewhere the majority in the party organizations remained with the SR party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] This was despite the Left SR's eventual opposition to the closure of the Constituent Assembly by the Bolsheviks.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Per Serge's account, 40 of 339 elected SR deputies were leftists and 50 belong to Chernov's centrist faction.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In 1917 the Central Committee of the Russian Social-Democratic Labour Party (Bolsheviks) had begun to allow mass membership, without consulting with Lenin.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] On July 1, 1917 the Central Committee sent out an instruction to local party organizations to build a broad democratic unity ahead of the elections, to reach out to Menshevik-Internationalists, left-wing SRs and trade unions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] With the election finally approaching, Lenin took a tough stance towards the Central Committee.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] He deplored the absence of proletarians from the list of proposed candidates that the Central Committee had adopted, charging the Committee with opening the doors for opportunists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In Lenin's view, only workers would be able to create alliances with the peasantry.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Russian Social-Democratic Labour Party (Bolsheviks) campaigned for bread, peace and a government of Soviets.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] But the party leadership was divided on the issue of the Constituent Assembly.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The moderates in the Central Committee held the opinion that the Constituent Assembly should become the supreme body to decide the future path of Russia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In an article edited after the elections, he stated that the proletariat cannot achieve victory if it does not win the majority of the population to its side.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] But to limit that winning to polling a majority of votes in an election under the rule of the bourgeoisie, or to make it the condition for it, is crass stupidity, or else sheer deception of the workers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Thirdly, it must entirely destroy the influence of the bourgeoisie and petty-bourgeois compromisers over the majority of the non-proletarian masses by satisfying their economic needs in a revolutionary way at the expense of the exploiters.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The party emerged victorious in the two main cities; Petrograd and Moscow, and emerged the major party in urban Russia overall.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] It won an absolute majority of votes in the Baltic Fleet, the Northern Front and the Western Front.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The call for immediate peace made the Bolsheviks popular in the military, winning around 42% of the votes from the armed forces.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] By the time of the election, the Mensheviks had lost most of their influence in the workers' soviets.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The election result confirmed the marginalization of the Mensheviks, who obtained a little over a million votes.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In a fifth of the constituencies, pro-war Mensheviks and Internationalists ran on competing slates and in Petrograd and Kharkov the defencists had set up their own local organizations.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Nearly half of the Menshevik vote came from Georgia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Kadet party had changed its name to 'People's Freedom Party' by 1917, but the new name was rarely used.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Kadets campaigned for national unity, law and order, honour commitments to the allies of Russia and 'honorable peace'.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Kadets condemned Bolsheviks in election campaign.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Kadets had sought to build a broad democratic coalition, setting up a liaison committee for alliances (Vladimir Dmitrievich Nabokov, Andrei Ivanovich Shingarev and M.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Adzhemov) but this effort failed as the Popular Socialists and cooperative movement rejected electoral pacts with the Kadets.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Whilst the Kadets emerged as the main losers in the election, they did take a sizable share of the votes in the largest cities.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] However the Kadets were hurt by abstention amongst urban intelligentsia voters.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] They had also lost a large share of their habitual Jewish intelligentsia vote to Jewish national coalition lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The congress of the Popular Socialists, held on September 26, 1917, rejected the notion of an electoral alliance with the Kadets.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The party congress ordered that joint lists would only be organized with fellow socialist groups.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Popular Socialists condemned the Bolsheviks in their campaigning, whilst stressing the defencist line of their own party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The cooperative societies held an emergency congress on October 4, 1917, at which it was decided that they would contest the Constituent Assembly elections directly.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The congress discarded the notion of electoral pacts with non-socialist groups.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In the Petrograd election district, the list of cooperative candidates included only one notable figure, Alexander Chayanov.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The other six candidates were largely unknown.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Most non-Russian voters opted for national minority parties.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In the case of Ukraine, the Ukrainian Socialist-Revolutionary Party dominated the 4 electoral districts of the Ukrainian peasantry.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Non-Ukrainian urban populations largely voted for Russian parties.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In the city of Kiev, the Ukrainian parties obtained 26% of the vote.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Over half a million soldiers and officers in the army and navy voted for Ukrainian parties supporting the Central Rada, making the Ukrainians the third force among military voters.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] However, in Belarus, Belarusian nationalist groups gathered less than 1% of the votes.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In Transcaucasus the vote was divided between Georgians (voting for the Mensheviks), Armenians (voting for the Armenian Revolutionary Federation, also known as *Dashnaksiun*) and Azerbaijanis (voting for Musavat and other Muslim groups).
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Tatar and Bashkir lists gathered 55% of the votes in Ufa.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In July 1917 the First All-Kazakh Congress was held, establishing the Alash Party as a national political party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The party called for the 'liberation of the Kazakh people from colonial yoke'.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Ahead of the election, party committees were formed in Semipalatinsk, Omsk, Akmolinsk and Uralsk.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In the Semirechie, Syr-Darya and Horde electoral districts Alash did not field lists of their own, but placed candidates of other Muslim lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Four days ahead of the vote the newspaper *Qazaq* published the Alash programme, including a call for a democratic federal republic with equality of nationalities.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In 14 electoral districts, 2 or more Jewish lists were in the fray.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In Zhitomir, 5 out of 13 parties contesting were Jewish.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In Gomel 4 out of 11 parties were Jewish, in Poltava 5 out of 14.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Some 80% of the votes cast for Jewish parties went to Jewish national coalition lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Folkspartey was the most enthusiastic proponent of Jewish national coalition lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] These coalitions, generally contesting under titles such as 'Jewish National Bloc' or 'Jewish National Election Committee' also gathered Zionists and Orthodox Jews.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The candidates on these lists had vowed to form a common bloc in the Constituent Assembly and implement decisions of the All-Russian Jewish Congress.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Jewish national lists were confronted by the various Jewish socialist parties; the General Jewish Labour Bund, the Jewish Social Democratic Labour Party (Poalei Zion) and the United Jewish Socialist Workers Party (*Fareynikte*).
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Bund carried out 200 electoral meetings in White Russia (with a total attendance of about 127,000), and in Ukraine the party held 2–3 electoral meetings weekly.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In Odessa confrontations between socialist and non-socialist Jewish parties led to physical violence.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Goldstein, the Moscow rabbi Yaakov Mazeh.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Gruzenberg (who was then close to Zionist circles).
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] David Lvovich was elected on SR-Fareynikte list and the Bundist G.I.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Lure was elected on a Menshevik-Bund list.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Buryat National Committee had previously been linked to the SRs, but ahead of the election relation was broken.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Buryat SRs were not given prominent places on candidate lists, and the Buryat National Committee ended up contesting on its own.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Radical Democrats (rightists) got some 19,000 votes.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] No fully complete account of the results of the 1917 election exists, as in several districts the holding of the election or the tallying of votes was interrupted.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The numbers in the table below represent accounts from the voting in 70 out of 81 electoral districts, although not all of those districts have complete voting tallies.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The tally of elected deputies stems from 74 districts.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Includes all joint Bolshevik/Menshevik-Internationalist lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Includes the joint Bolshevik-Menshevik list in Vologda, but not the joint Menshevik-Bolshevik list in Tobolsk (as the latter was reportedly dominated by Mensheviks).
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Includes joint Menshevik-Bund lists, and the joint Menshevik-Bolshevik list in Tobolsk.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] This line does not include the votes from the joint SR-Menshevik list in Olonets, which elected one Menshevik deputy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] However, the Menshevik from Olonets is included in the seat count.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Includes the joint list with the Cheremi National Union in Vyatka, which elected the sole Popular Socialist deputy nationwide.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The various alliances with cooperative movements and other socialist groups are listed separately.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Includes the different rightist and monarchist lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In many constituencies the party contested on the Ukrainian SR-led lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] This count is only for the 2 districts where the Ukrainian Social Democrats contested alone.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Various local alliances of Popular Socialists, cooperatives, right-wing Mensheviks, right-wing SRs, Plekhanov's Unity group, etc.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In most constituencies where the Bund was active, it contested on joint lists with the Mensheviks.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] This line only counts the 3 constituencies were the Bund ran its own lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Includes the leftist dissident lists, that contested against the official SR party lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In locations where the left faction of the SRs dominated the official party list, the result is included in the main SR count.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In many locations the Folkspartei joined Jewish national lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Includes 4 Ukrainian lists, outside of Ukraine, with unclear party identity.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] There are various different accounts of the election result, with varying numbers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Many accounts on the election result originate from N.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Svyatitsky's account, who was himself elected as an SR deputy to the Constituent Assembly.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] His article was included in the one-year anniversary symposium of the Russian Revolution organized by the SR party (Moscow, Zemlya i Volya Publishers, 1918).
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Lenin (1919) describes Svyatitsky's account as extremely interesting.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] It presented results from 54 electoral districts, covering most of European Russia and Siberia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Notably is lacked details from the Olonets, Estonian, Kaluga, Bessarabian, Podolsk, Orenburg, Yakutsk, Don governorates, as well as Transcaucasus.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] All in all, Svyatitsky's account includes 36,257,960 votes.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] According to Lenin, the actual number from said 54 electoral districts was 36,262,560 votes.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] But Lenin reaffirms that between Svyatitisky's article and his account, the number of votes cast by party is largely identical.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] More recent studies often use Svyatitsky's 1918 account as their starting point for further elaboration.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Spirin (1987) uses local newspapers and Russian, Belarusian and Ukrainian archival holdings to supplement Svyatitsky, whereas U.S. historian Oliver Henry Radkey predominately uses local newspapers as sources.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] According to Rabinovitch (2016), Spirin's account is the most complete.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] According to Arato (2017), U.S. scholar Radkey is the most serious historian on the 1917 election.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Another 55 deputies were supposed to have been elected from another 8 electoral districts.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Of the over 700 deputies known by name, over 400 participated at first session and only session of the Constituent Assembly (240 of the assembled belonged to the SR bloc).
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Several prominent politicians had stood as candidates in multiple electoral districts.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The Central Committee of the Russian Social-Democratic Labour Party (Bolsheviks) had named Lenin as their candidate in 5 districts: Petrograd City, Petrograd Province, Ufa, Baltic Fleet and Northern Front.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Lenin was also nominated from Moscow City.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] On November 27 (December 10) the All-Russia Committee for Elections to the Constituent Assembly requested members of the Constituent Assembly who had been returned by several areas to present a written statement indicating the electoral district for which they accepted election.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Having been elected by several areas, Lenin, too, presented such a statement.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] Lenin opted to represent the Baltic Fleet in the Constituent Assembly.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] In case an elected candidate didn't send in such a statement, the All-Russian Election Commission for the Constituent Assembly would consider the person elected from the district where he obtained the highest number of votes.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] The All Russian Constituent Assembly (Всероссийское Учредительное собрание, Vserossiyskoye Uchreditelnoye sobraniye) convened only for 13 hours, from 4 p.m. to 5 a.m., 18–19 January [O.S.
[src:alexander-kerensky/1917-russian-constituent-assembly-election] 5–6 January] 1918, whereupon it was dissolved by the Bolshevik-controlled All-Russian Central Executive Committee, making the Bolshevik Third All-Russian Congress of Soviets the new governing body of Russia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The **20th Century Press Archives** (German: *Pressearchiv 20.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert*) comprises about 19 million newspaper clippings, organized in folders about persons, companies, wares, events and topics.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] It originates from the Hamburg Kolonialinstitut (colonial institute) founded in 1908.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Within the Hamburg Institute of International Economics (HWWA) it turned into a unique public press archive.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] In 2007 it was absorbed by the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) and merged with the Wirtschaftsarchiv (economics archive) of the Kiel Institute for the World Economy (IfW), founded in 1914.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Article collection was discontinued at the end of 2005, but the archive is still open to the public.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The archive has its origins in two institutions in the German cities of Hamburg and Kiel.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] In Hamburg, after a few years, the "Zentralstelle" (central office) of the Kolonialinstitut was transformed from a free information center for colonial issues into a comprehensive archive of global political and economic topics, which primarily supported the city's merchants.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] After the breakdown of the German colonial empire in World War I, the renaming to "Hamburgisches Welt-Wirtschafts-Archiv" in 1919 sealed this reorientation.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The staff of HWWA reflected its importance and grew from 54 in 1919 to 183 permanent or temporary employees in 1958 – a number that seems to have remained largely stable until the late 1990s.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Founded shortly before the outbreak of the First World War, the Kiel Economic Archive and its library were closely linked to the scientific work of the IfW, which focused on global economic contexts and their practical use.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] In 1966, the library of the IfW was given the function of a central library for economics by the German Research Foundation (DFG) in the Federal Republic of Germany, and in 1993, the department was renamed accordingly.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] During the first and second world wars, both archives were intensively involved in the foreign and wartime planning of the empire and the Nazi state.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Starting in 1936, "Confidential Reports from the Foreign Press" provided selected economic leaders and Nazi departments with "largely unfiltered information and comments on economic issues from foreign media and represented a unique feature in Nazi media policy".
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Acting with the informal means of a foreign cultural and information policy supplementing the military expansion policy, HWWA and IfW dedicated their services to the Nazi regime.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] In 1996, a closer cooperation between HWWA and ZBW / Wirtschaftsarchiv began, with the aim of merging the two archives.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] From the beginning of 2001, the articles were indexed according to a new common classification system and made retrievable via a reference database, "EconPress".
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Following a recommendation from an evaluation within the Leibniz Association in 2003, the current press documentation was finished at the end of 2005 and the materials were frozen at that point.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The separate existence of the HWWA ended in 2007 with the integration of its press documentation and library into the ZBW as a newly formed foundation under public law.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Today, the press archive belongs to the (research) organisations of the Leibniz Association.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] By 1919 at the latest, the Hamburg archive collected "press clippings on a global scale".
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] More than 1400 sources were monitored for the press archives.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Their broad international distribution provides access to the history of political thought and receptive history of the covered topics.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Occasionally, the collected publications go back as far as 1826.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] While the persons archive was only available in paper form until its partial digitization, the holdings of the topics, wares and companies archives were saved every ten years on roll film or microfiche since the 1960s and then the paper clippings were pulped.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The holdings of the Kiel Wirtschaftsarchiv are less comprehensively documented.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The "war archive" of 1914–1918, which amounted to one million clippings, was destroyed by a bomb strike in 1942.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] In 1958, when six scientific experts and more than 30 employees in total were collecting and organizing the material, the total extent of the archive was estimated as more than three million, and in 1993 as more than ten million.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert* application, parts of the holdings of both archives are now accessible on the web.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] From 2004 to 2007, the German Research Foundation funded a project to digitize parts of the archives, namely the materials from the beginning up to 1949 (the formation of the Federal Republic of Germany).
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The paper clippings from the folders of the persons archive were scanned, and metadata (folder and document ID as well as page number, occasionally also source, publication date, author and title) were recorded by project staff.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Optical character recognition could not be applied due to the partially used Fraktur scripts, the constantly changing fonts (as well as languages) in the sequence of the articles, and the sometimes poor quality of the clippings.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] However, the approximately 5,500 person folders created before 1949 are fully accessible online.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The roll film parts of the archive (up to 1960) have also been digitized.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] As neither the folders nor the documents on these films were separated in a machine-readable fashion, such formal elements could not be automatically derived.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Instead, the pages had to be "sliced" with specially developed "Slider" software, assembled into documents and folders, and given metadata.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Only a small part of this labor-intensive process was finished at the end of the project in 2007.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] It is continued today, so that new folders are continually made available via the web application "Pressemappe 20.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert", which was created within the framework of the project.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] 11,000 company folders on digitized roll film, by 2018 about 7,500 were accessible online.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] For the topics and wares archives, the proportion of online folders seems to be significantly lower.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The persons are alphabetically indexed by name, while the companies are accessible by name, geographically by their headquarters and via industry lists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The topics can be accessed via the topics hierarchy and country system as well as through a search for subject and geographical GND keywords, and via a world map with geolocations.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] The limitation to 1949 was made for capacity reasons, and due to intellectual property rights restrictions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] Numerous individual articles within the dossiers are subject to blocking notices if the death of the author (or in the case of anonymous or pseudonymous works, the date of publication) is less than 70 years ago.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] With a moving wall more and more documents should be released over time.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] How many of the about 5.7 million documents digitized in the context of the project are accessible to the scientific and general public on the web is not known.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] In 2019, the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) placed all the metadata of the archives under a CC0 licence, and began a cooperation and "data donation" with Wikimedia Deutschland.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] This led to the creation of many new Wikidata items and the enrichment of many existing items; by the end of 2022, every folder in the archive was connected to items in Wikidata.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] In 2024, changes to intellectual property rights in Europe made it possible to provide complete digitized images from the archive – some 3.8 million pages – for online viewing within the European Union.
[src:alexander-kerensky/20th-century-press-archives] A volunteer project is working on adding links to the archive's folders in Wikidata, so that Wikidata provides an index to the material.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The borough of Manhattan in New York City contains 214 numbered east–west streets ranging from 1st to 228th, the majority of them designated in the Commissioners' Plan of 1811.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] These streets do not run exactly east–west, because the grid plan is aligned with the Hudson River, rather than with the cardinal directions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Thus, the majority of the Manhattan grid's "west" is approximately 29 degrees north of true west; the angle differs above 155th Street, where the grid initially ended.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The grid now covers the length of the island from 14th Street north.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] All numbered streets carry an East or West prefix – for example, East 10th Street or West 10th Street – which is demarcated at Broadway below 8th Street, and at Fifth Avenue at 8th Street and above.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The numbered streets carry crosstown traffic.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] In general, but with numerous exceptions, even-numbered streets are one-way eastbound and odd-numbered streets are one-way westbound.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Most wider streets, and a few of the narrow ones, carry two-way traffic.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Although the numbered streets begin just north of East Houston Street in the East Village, they generally do not extend west into Greenwich Village, which already had established, named streets when the grid plan was laid out by the Commissioners' Plan of 1811.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Some streets in that area that do continue farther west change direction before reaching the Hudson River.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The highest numbered street on Manhattan Island is 220th Street, but Marble Hill is also within the borough of Manhattan, so the highest street number in the borough is 228th Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The numbering system continues in the Bronx, up to 263rd Street, though east of Van Cortlandt Park the system ends at 243rd Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The lowest numbered street in Manhattan is East 1st Street, which runs through Alphabet City near East Houston Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] There are also three streets numbered as First, Second and Third Place in Battery Park City.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] East 1st Street begins just north of East Houston Street at Avenue A and continues to the Bowery.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Peretz Square, a small triangular sliver park where Houston Street, First Street and First Avenue meet marks the spot where the grid takes hold.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] East 2nd Street begins just north of East Houston Street at Avenue C and also continues to the Bowery.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The east end of East 3rd, 4th, 5th, and 7th streets is Avenue D, with East 6th Street continuing further eastward and connecting to the FDR Drive.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The west end of most of these streets is the Bowery and Third Avenue, except for 3rd Street (formerly Amity Place), which continues to Sixth Avenue; and 4th Street, which extends west and then north to 13th Street in Greenwich Village.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Great Jones Street connects East 3rd to West 3rd.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] East 5th Street goes west to Cooper Square, but is interrupted between Avenues B and C by The Earth School and Public School 364, and between First Avenue and Avenue A by the Village View Apartments.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] East 6th Street contains many Indian restaurants between First and Second Avenues and is sometimes known as Curry Row.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 8th and 9th streets run parallel to each other, beginning at Avenue D, interrupted by Tompkins Square Park at Avenue B, resuming at Avenue A and continuing to Sixth Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] West 8th Street is an important local shopping street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 8th Street between Avenue A and Third Avenue is called St Mark's Place, but it is counted in the length below.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The M8 bus route operates eastbound on 8th Street and westbound on 9th Street between Avenue A and Sixth Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 8th Street has one subway station: Eighth Street–New York University, served by the N, R and W Trains.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Amos, Hammond, and Troy Streets were in the Greenwich Village street grid before 1811.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] In the middle 19th century they were renamed as the western parts of West 10th, 11th and 12th Streets, respectively.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Additionally, **Little West 12th Street** runs parallel to West 13th Street from West Street to the northeast corner of Ninth Avenue and Gansevoort Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 14th Street is a main numbered street in Manhattan.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It begins at Avenue C and ends at West Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] From Avenue A or Avenue C to West Street there is service M14A/D bus.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] At 6th Avenue, there is a PATH stop with service to Midtown Manhattan and New Jersey.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Traffic on 15th Street moves from east to west.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The street formerly started at the FDR Drive, but most of the street between the Drive and Avenue C was permanently closed, as was the 15th Street exit from the Drive, after the September 11 attacks, due to the presence of the Con Edison East River Generating Station there.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Only Con Edison personnel have access to the closed portion.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The street is then interrupted by Stuyvesant Town from Avenue C to First Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It then continues to Union Square East (Park Avenue South) where it is interrupted by Union Square It picks up again at Union Square West, and continues unimpeded to Eleventh Avenue at the Hudson River.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Traffic on 16th Street moves from west to east.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It starts at Eleventh Avenue at the Hudson River, and runs until it is interrupted at Union Square West (Broadway) by Union Square.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It picks up again on the other side of the park at Union Square East (Park Avenue South), but is shortly stopped again by Stuyvesant Square from between Second and Third Avenues (Rutherford Place) to between First and Second Avenues (Perlman Place).
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] At First Avenue, it is interrupted by Stuyvesant Town, and starts up again at Avenue C.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It then dead ends between that avenue and the FDR Drive.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 17th, 18th and 19th streets start at First Avenue and finish at Eleventh Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It forms the northern borders of both Union Square (between Broadway and Park Avenue South) and Stuyvesant Square.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Composer Antonín Dvořák's New York home was located at 327 East 17th Street, near Perlman Place.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The house was razed by Beth Israel Medical Center after it received approval of a 1991 application to demolish the house and replace it with an AIDS hospice with financing from the photographer Robert Mapplethorpe.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] *Time* Magazine was started at 141 East 17th Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 18th Street has a local subway station at the crossing with Seventh Avenue, served by the 1 (and the 2 at late nights) on the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] There used to be an 18th Street station on the IRT Lexington Avenue Line at the crossing with Park Avenue South.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] This street is home to the IAC Building, designed by Frank Gehry.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 19th Street travels west for most of its length, except between Tenth and Eleventh Avenues the travel direction is reversed and traffic flows east.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 20th Street starts at Avenue C, and 21st and 22nd Streets begin at First Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Travel on the last block of the 20th, 21st, and 22nd streets, between Tenth and Eleventh Avenues, is in the opposite direction than it is on the rest of the respective street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 20th Street is very wide from the Avenue C to First Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Along the southern perimeter of Gramercy Park, between Gramercy Park East and Gramercy Park West, 20th Street is known as Gramercy Park South.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Between Second and Third Avenues, 21st Street is alternatively known as Police Officer Anthony Sanchez Way.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Along the northern perimeter of Gramercy Park, between Gramercy Park East and Gramercy Park West, 21st Street is known as Gramercy Park North.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 23rd Street is another main numbered street in Manhattan.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It begins at Avenue C/FDR Drive and ends at Eleventh Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Additionally, there is the M23 Select Bus Service, running through the length of 23rd Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] A small portion of 24th Street exists between First Avenue and East Midtown Plaza ending at a dead end before Second Avenue, a second portion is between East Midtown Plaza and Madison Avenue, ending because of Madison Square Park.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 25th Street, which is in three parts, starts at FDR Drive, is a pedestrian plaza between Third Avenue and Lexington Avenue, and ends at Madison.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Then West 24th and 25th streets continue from Fifth Avenue to Eleventh Avenue (25th) or Twelfth Avenue (24th).
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The two cul-de-sacs on 24th Street between First and Second avenues were created in the late 1960s to connect the northern and southern blocks of East Midtown Plaza with a mid-block pedestrian plaza having a focal point on St.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The pedestrian plaza on 25th Street between Third and Lexington avenues, named the "Clivner=Field Plaza", was completed in 2021 and provides outdoor space for the campus of Baruch College.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 26th Street is all in one part and after reaching FDR Drive bends and runs parallel to FDR Drive up to 30th Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Some of the most notable venues are Bungalow 8, Marquee, Suzie Wong, Cain, and Pink Elephant.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 27th and continuing down almost the entire rest of the block, the former warehouse spaces of clubs Twilo, Guesthouse, Home, Bed, and more have been repurposed by British immersive theater group Punchdrunk as The McKittrick Hotel, the site of their theatrical experience *Sleep No More*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Heading east, 27th Street passes through Chelsea Park between Tenth and Ninth Avenues, with the Fashion Institute of Technology (FIT) on the corner of Eighth.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] On Madison Avenue between 26th and 27th streets, on the site of the old Madison Square Garden, is the New York Life Building, built in 1928 and designed by Cass Gilbert, with a square tower topped by a striking gilded pyramid.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Twenty-Seventh Street passes one block north of Madison Square Park and culminates at Bellevue Hospital on First Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The segment of 27th Street east of Second Avenue is a pedestrian mall and passes through Bellevue South Park.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 30th Street runs uninterrupted across the island from 12th Avenue to FDR Drive.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It is the southern terminus of Dyer Avenue and thus also of the Lincoln Tunnel's eastern approach.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] There is also an elevator with access to the High Line on the West Side.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Tisch Hospital is bounded on the south by 30th Street between 1st Avenue and FDR Drive.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The segment of 30th Street between First and Second avenues was widened by 20 feet (6.1 m) in the 1950s when the superblock for Kips Bay Towers was created.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] On the East Side, both streets end at Second Avenue, where the street grid is interrupted by superblocks containing Kips Bay Towers and NYU Medical Center.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Francis of Assisi is situated at 135–139 West 31st Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] At 210 West is the Capuchin Monastery of St.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] At the corner of Broadway and West 31st Street is the Grand Hotel.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The former Hotel Pierrepont was located at 43 West 32nd Street, The Continental NYC tower is at the corner of Sixth Avenue and 32nd Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 29 East 32nd Street was the location of the first building owned by the Grolier Club between 1890 and 1917.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] In 2017, the segment of 32nd Street between Second and Third avenues was co-named "Ms.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Magazine Way" in honor of the location where the publication was launched at 207 East 32nd Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 33rd Street runs uninterrupted from First Avenue to Seventh Avenue where it turns into a pedestrian road for a quarter of a block and turns back into a street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Then it runs the rest of the way to 12th Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It runs on the north side of Hudson Yards and the south side of the Empire State Building.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The segment of 33rd Street between First and Second avenues was widened by 20 feet (6.1 m) in the 1950s when the superblock for Kips Bay Towers was created.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] In 2018, the same street segment was converted from one-way to two-way traffic to improve access for ambulances traveling to emergency entrance of NYU Langone Health on First Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] At Park Avenue, 33rd Street was closed to westbound through traffic beginning in 1999, when barriers were installed at the southern end of the Park Avenue Tunnel.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] In 2019, the segment of 33rd Street between Tenth and Eleventh avenues was reconstructed as part of the Hudson Yards Redevelopment Project, which included raising the street elevation by up to 15 feet (4.6 m) for integration with Hudson Boulevard.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 35th Street runs from FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Notable locations include East River Ferry, Mercy University Manhattan Campus, and the Jacob K.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 36th Street runs from the FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It runs on the south side of the Queens–Midtown Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit and over the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Notable locations on 36th Street are the American Copper Buildings, Sniffen Court, The Morgan Library & Museum, Gotham Hall, and the Javits Center.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 37th Street runs from the FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It runs on the north side of the Queens–Midtown Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit and over the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Notable locations on 37th Street are the Corinthian, the Morgan Library & Museum, Gotham Hall, and the Javits Center.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 38th Street runs from FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It runs on the south side of the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Notable locations on 38th Street are The Corinthian, The Town House Hotel, 425 Fifth Avenue, and the Javits Center.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 39th Street runs from First Avenue to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It runs over the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] A notable location on 39th Street is the Astro's Dog Run.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] A portion of West 46th Street between Eighth and Ninth Avenues is nicknamed **Restaurant Row**, after the number of restaurants located along its length.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Mayor John Lindsay had designated the street as Restaurant Row in 1973, honoring 16 restaurants on the block.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The Mount Vernon Hotel Museum, one of only eight surviving pre-1800 buildings in Manhattan, is located at 421 East 61st Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The Pierre, a luxury hotel opened in 1930, is at 2 East 61st Street, at the intersection with Fifth Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The Gateway School, an independent school for children aged 5 to 14 with learning disabilities, is located at 211 West 61st Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The Consulate-General of Russia in New York City was opened at 7–9 East 61st Street in 1933 and closed in 1948.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] East 77th and 78th streets run normally west of York Avenue, but east of York Avenue, 77th runs east, and 78th runs west, to accommodate the Pavilion at 500 East 77th.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The FDR Drive has an exit at 78th and an entrance at 79th.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] At the corner of 77th and York, on which sits PS 158, pedestrians cross 77th on red and wait on the green on the east side of York.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] As with all of Manhattan's numbered streets from 60th to 109th Street, 80th Street is divided by Central Park into eastern and western sections.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Traffic on 80th Street, on both sides of the park, runs west to east.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] West 80th Street begins at Riverside Drive on the Upper West Side, then passes West End Avenue, Broadway, and Amsterdam Avenue, then stops at Columbus Avenue when it reaches the grounds on the American Museum of Natural History.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Significant buildings on West 80th Street include those in the Riverside Drive–West 80th–81st Street Historic District, on both sides of the street's block between Riverside Drive and West End Avenue, such as the "Gothicesque" row houses at 307–317 West 80th Street designed by Charles H.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Israels, and those at 319–323 West 80th Street designed by Clarence F.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] True also designed the "vaguely Georgian" 328 West 80th Street on the same block, which also contains George F.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Pelham II's 411 West End Avenue, an Art Deco apartment building.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] East 80th Street begins at Fifth Avenue on the Upper East Side and continues past Madison, Park, Lexington, and Third, where it enters the section of the Upper East Side called Yorkville.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It then continues past Second, First, York and East End Avenues before dead-ending at the FDR Drive.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Significant buildings on East 80th Street include the American Irish Historical Society at 991 Fifth Avenue; the houses of Franklyn and Edna Woolworth and her two sisters at 2, 4, and 6 East 80th Street, built by F.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Gilbert; the postmodern 45 East 80th Street at Madison Avenue, designed by Liebman Liebman & Associates; the raw concrete 1967 Manhattan Church of Christ by Eggers & Higgins; 52 East 80th Street between Madison and Park, built in the 1890s.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Schmidt; and the same designer's Vincent and Helen Astor House at #130, built in 1927–28 and now the Junior League of the City of New York.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] At 1157 Lexington Avenue is the 1932 Unitarian Church of All Souls, designed by Robert Upjohn.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The first segment, West 90th Street begins at Riverside Drive and ends at Central Park West or West Drive, when it is open, in Central Park on the Upper West Side.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The second segment of East 90th Street begins at East Drive, at Engineers Gate of Central Park.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] When East Drive is closed, East 90th Street begins at Fifth Avenue on the Upper East Side and curves to the right at the FDR Drive becoming East End Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Our Lady of Good Counsel Church, is located on East 90th Street between Third Avenue and Second Avenue, across the street from Ruppert Towers (1601 and 1619 Third Avenue) and Ruppert Park.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Asphalt Green is a nonprofit community center dedicated to sports, fitness, and wellness located on East 90th Street between York Avenue and East End Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Above 114th Street between Amsterdam Avenue and Morningside Drive, there is a private indoor pedestrian bridge connecting two buildings on the campus of Mount Sinai Morningside.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 17 East 126th Street was the location of Art Kane's 1958 photograph of contemporary jazz musicians, now known as *A Great Day in Harlem*, which featured in the 2004 Steven Spielberg film *The Terminal*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The 132nd Street Community Garden is located on 132nd Street between Adam Clayton Powell Jr.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] In 1997, the lot received a garden makeover; the Borough President's office funded the installation of a $100,000 water distribution system that keeps the wide variety of trees green.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The garden also holds a goldfish pond and several benches.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The spirit of the neighborhood lives in gardens like this one, planted and tended by local residents.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The Manhattanville Bus Depot (formerly known as the **132nd Street Bus Depot**) is located on West 132nd and 133rd Street between Broadway and Riverside Drive in the Manhattanville neighborhood.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 155th Street starts on the West Side at Riverside Drive, crossing Broadway, Amsterdam Avenue and St.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Nicholas Place, the terrain drops off steeply, and 155th Street is carried on a 1,600-foot (490 m) long viaduct, a City Landmark constructed in 1893, that slopes down towards the Harlem River, continuing onto the Macombs Dam Bridge, crossing over (but not intersecting with) the Harlem River Drive.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] A separate, unconnected section of 155th Street runs under the viaduct, connecting Bradhurst Avenue and the Harlem River Drive.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The New York City Subway serves 155th Street on the IND Eighth Avenue and Concourse Lines.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] West of Fort Washington Avenue, 181st Street is largely residential, bordering Hudson Heights and having a few shops to serve the local residents.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] East of Fort Washington Avenue, the street becomes increasingly commercial, becoming dominated entirely by retail stores where the street reaches Broadway and continues as such until reaching the Harlem River.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It is the area's major shopping district.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 181st Street is served by two New York City Subway lines; there is a 181st Street station at Fort Washington Avenue on the IND Eighth Avenue Line (A train) and a 181st Street station at St.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Nicholas Avenue on the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line (1 train).
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The stations are about 500 metres (550 yd) from each other and are not connected.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The George Washington Bridge Bus Terminal is a couple of blocks south on Fort Washington Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 181st Street is also the last south/west exit in New York on the Trans-Manhattan Expressway (I-95), just before crossing the George Washington Bridge to New Jersey.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 187th Street intersects with, from east to west, Laurel Hill Terrace, Amsterdam Avenue, Audubon Avenue, St.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Nicholas Avenue, Wadsworth Avenue, Broadway, Bennett Avenue, Overlook Terrace, Fort Washington Avenue, Pinehurst Avenue, Cabrini Boulevard and Chittenden Avenue.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The many institutions on 187th Street include Mount Sinai Jewish Center, the Dombrov Shtiebel, and the uptown campus of Yeshiva University.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The local public elementary and middle school P.S./M.S.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 187 is located on Cabrini Boulevard, just north of 187th Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The Dyckman Street station was formerly called "Dyckman Street–200th Street", but there has never been a street in Manhattan with that number.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] A 196th street does exist, between Broadway and Ellwood Street.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] It is the only street between what would be 193rd and 201st to have numbered signage.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The University Heights Bridge, a swing bridge across the Harlem River, connects the street with Fordham Road in the Bronx.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] While 208th Street exists as a small driveway and parking lot located just south of the 207th Street Yard, Manhattan has no streets numbered 209th or 210th.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Manhattan has no streets numbered 221st, 222nd, 223rd, or 224th, as their theoretical location is taken up by the Spuyten Duyvil Creek.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] Despite having streets numbered 225th, 227th and 228th in the Marble Hill neighborhood, Manhattan has no street numbered 226th.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] 228th Street, located in the Marble Hill neighborhood, is the highest numbered street in Manhattan.
[src:alexander-kerensky/91st-street-manhattan] The street numbers continue in The Bronx.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] From 1928, the National Broadcasting Service, as part of the federal Postmaster-General's Department, gradually took over responsibility for all the existing stations that were sponsored by public licence fees ("A" Class licences).
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The outsourced Australian Broadcasting Company supplied programs from 1929.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In 1932 a commission was established, merging the original ABC company and the National Broadcasting Service.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] It is from this time that Radio National dates as a distinct network within the ABC, in which a system of program relays was developed during the subsequent decades to link stations spread across the nation.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The beginnings of Radio National lie with Sydney radio station 2FC, which aired its first test broadcast on 5 December 1923 and officially went to air on 9 January 1924.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] 2FC stood for Farmer and Company, the original owner of the station before the ABC bought the station in 1937.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The ABC then rolled out a national network across the country, somewhat similar in nature to the BBC National Programme.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The first transmitters for 2FC, 5CL and 4QG were made by AWA with power of 5 kW They used a MT7A valve for the final high power RF stage and a MT7B for the modulator.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The power supply was 12,000 volts from three-phase power rectified by MR7 valves.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] 4QG commenced with a 500 Watt transmitter which continued for about 6 months until the 5 kW unit was commissioned.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The radio transmitters for 3AR and 2FC were upgraded to 10 kW in a contract let in 1938 to STC.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The transmitters were designed by Charles Strong in London, and were notable in using negative feedback to ensure a high quality flat frequency response.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The power level of 2FC and 3AR was upgraded to 50 kW in the early 1950s.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The transmitters for these were housed in the same building as the Radio 1 network.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The final stage contained three parallel 3J/261E air cooled triodes running in class C amplifier at 90% efficiency.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] These were driven by a class B push-pull modulator with the same type of valves.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In the 1970s, the network's program format began to take on a more serious tone, a style which continues to this day.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Art critic Peter Timms later remarked that the network is "virtually the only non-print media forum for art in this country".
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In the early 1980s the broadcast footprint was extended with the construction of the first of over 300 regional FM transmitters (including community re-broadcast sites).
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In 1985, the ABC renamed "Radio 2" as "Radio National".
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Since 1990, all Radio National stations have had the same callsign, "RN".
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] As a result of cuts in the 1996–97 budget, Radio National was hit with a reduction of a million dollars in its funding, with a significant impact on programming.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In 2008, controversial programming changes once more raised the issue of funding cuts to the public broadcaster.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Presenter Stephen Crittenden leaked confidential programming changes in an unscheduled live broadcast before the start of his show, criticising his superiors.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] He was suspended for his outburst, and his unscripted comments were cut from Radio National's podcast and transcript of the program.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Religious commentator Paul Collins on crikey.com subsequently echoed Crittenden's fears.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Crittenden was reinstated in 2009 as a reporter on *Background Briefing*, after a settlement was reached.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] However, his program and the other eight programs that had been cancelled or merged were not re-instated that year.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The head of ABC Radio, Sue Howard, was dismissed in 2009.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In January 2012 Radio National was rebranded as RN, partly in recognition of the station's growing digital audience.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] RN has also been used as shorthand for the station's name by many presenters going back several years.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] RN's tagline, which has changed regularly over the years, was also changed to "Your World Unfolding" to mesh with the station's new logo and visual identity.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In 2012 a new *Religion and Ethics Report* was launched, hosted by Andrew West.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The *Media Report* was also relaunched, hosted by broadcaster and former Life Matters host Richard Aedy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The *Media Report* was, however, cancelled again in 2015.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In late 2016, the new head of the ABC Michelle Guthrie defended the removal of staff and programmes from the Radio National 2017 schedule, with the scope of the new year's lineup culled due to budget cuts with consequent staff and programming reductions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In November 2024, Radio National announced new programmes and schedule designed to relaunch the station in 2025 as "the centre of big conversations and create a space where audiences can expand their worldview while engaging with the world’s best thinkers".
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] This was the biggest slate of changes and the largest announcement of new programmes since the 2017 upheaval and cuts.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The new programming schedule commenced on 20 January 2025.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The station also changed its logo from the previous "RN" logo to a new "Radio National" logo.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The new *Breakfast* format now included news presenter Luke Siddham Dundon, Canberra-based political correspondent Melissa Clarke and business correspondent Peter Ryan in addition to Sara.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] The program was changed to model BBC Radio 4's *Today* programme, with more serious national and international news covered, as well as live crosses to Clarke and Ryan for politics and business coverage throughout the programme.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] As part of the change to the schedule, some long-running programmes were cancelled.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Afternoon news magazine programme *RN Drive* was also axed in favour of Kelly's *Radio National Hour,* with host Andy Park now hosting the daily afternoon news and current affair show *The World Today*, previously hosted by Sara.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Economics programme *The Money*, hosted by Richard Aedy, was cancelled and replaced by new programme *The Economy, Stupid* hosted by Peter Martin.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Lifestyle and design programme *Blueprint for Living* was discontinued, with host Jonathan Green now hosting a new weekly food programme, *Every Bite*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Rural affairs news magazine programme *Australia Wide* (which previously aired at 6:30 p.m. weeknights) is no longer broadcast on Radio National, with Kelly's programme broadcasting during its previous time slot.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] *Australia Wide* is still broadcast on ABC Local Radio stations in regional areas outside capital cities.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In May 2025, Radio National announced a new annual countdown called the Top 100 Books, similar to Triple J's Hottest 100.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Each year will have a different theme, with the 2025 countdown being the Top 100 Books of the 21st Century.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] In 2026, Radio National further tweaked their program schedule particularly its arts, science and global affairs programs.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Radio National broadcasts national programming in subjects that include news and current affairs, the arts, social issues, science, drama and comedy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Some programs are relayed on Radio Australia, the ABC's international broadcasting service which was transmitted on shortwave until January 2017, as well as 24-hour FM stations, local relay stations and live satellite.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] All radio programs are available for live streaming over the Internet, and most (excluding drama, poetry and music) as audio-on-demand, or for download as MP3s for at least four weeks after broadcast.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Some programs are available as MP3s going back to 2005, when Radio National commenced podcasting.
[src:alexander-kerensky/abc-radio-national] Some of the following programs, listed in order of start date, are aired on both Radio National and ABC Local Radio networks.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was born in Braunau am Inn in Austria-Hungary and moved to Germany in 1913.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He was decorated during his service in the German Army in the First World War, receiving the Iron Cross.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1919, he joined the German Workers' Party (DAP), the precursor of the Nazi Party, and in 1921, was appointed the leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, he attempted to seize governmental power in a failed coup in Munich and was sentenced to five years in prison, serving just over a year.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, he dictated the first volume of his autobiography and political manifesto *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] After his early release in 1924, he gained popular support by attacking the Treaty of Versailles as well as promoting pan-Germanism, antisemitism, and anti-communism with charismatic oratory and Nazi propaganda.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He frequently denounced communism as being part of an international Jewish conspiracy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] By November 1932, the Nazi Party held the most seats in the *Reichstag*, but not a majority.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Former chancellor Franz von Papen and other conservative politicians convinced President Paul von Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as chancellor on 30 January 1933.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly thereafter, on 23 March, the *Reichstag* passed the Enabling Act of 1933, which ultimately began the Weimar Republic's transformation into Nazi Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Upon Hindenburg's death on 2 August 1934, Hitler replaced him as head of state and thereafter transformed Germany into a totalitarian dictatorship.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Domestically, Hitler implemented numerous racist policies and sought to deport or kill German Jews.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] His first six years in power resulted in rapid economic recovery from the Great Depression, the abrogation of restrictions imposed on Germany after the First World War, and the annexation of territories inhabited by millions of ethnic Germans, which initially gave him significant popular support.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] One of Hitler's key goals was *Lebensraum* (lit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] 'living space') for the German people in Eastern Europe.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] His aggressive, expansionist foreign policy is considered the primary cause of World War II in Europe.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 September 1939, Hitler oversaw the German invasion of Poland, thereby causing Britain and France to declare war on Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] After ordering an invasion of the Soviet Union in June 1941, he declared war on the United States in December of the same year.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of 1941, German forces and the European Axis powers occupied most of Europe and North Africa.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] These gains were gradually reversed after 1941 until the Allied forces defeated the German military in 1945.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 29 April 1945, Hitler married his longtime partner, Eva Braun, in the *Führerbunker* in Berlin.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] They committed suicide the next day to avoid capture by the Soviet Red Army.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The historian and biographer Ian Kershaw described Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Under Hitler's leadership and racist ideology, the Nazi regime was responsible for the genocide of an estimated six million Jews and millions of other victims, whom he and his followers deemed *Untermenschen* (lit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazis were also responsible for the deliberate killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of civilians killed during World War II was unprecedented in warfare, and the casualties make it the deadliest conflict in history.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's father, Alois Hitler, was the illegitimate child of Maria Schicklgruber.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The baptismal register did not show the name of his father, and Alois initially bore his mother's surname, "Schicklgruber".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1842, Johann Georg Hiedler married Alois's mother.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was brought up in the family of Hiedler's brother, Johann Nepomuk Hiedler.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois worked as a civil servant from 1855 until his retirement in 1895.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1876, Alois was made legitimate and his baptismal record annotated by a priest to register Johann Georg Hiedler as Alois's father (recorded as "Georg Hitler").
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois then assumed the surname "Hitler", also spelled "Hiedler", "Hüttler", or "Huettler".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The name is probably based on the German word *Hütte* (lit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] 'hut'), and has the meaning "one who lives in a hut".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi official Hans Frank suggested that Alois's mother had been employed as a housekeeper by a Jewish family in Graz, and that the family's 19-year-old son Leopold Frankenberger had fathered Alois, a claim that came to be known as the Frankenberger thesis.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] No Frankenberger was registered in Graz during that period, and no record has been produced of a Leopold Frankenberger's existence, so historians dismiss the claim that Alois's father was Jewish.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 2025, blood from the sofa in Hitler's study was used by Turi King of the University of Bath for DNA analysis.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The blood was confirmed to be Hitler's by comparing it to that of a male-line relative, and the DNA analysis also showed that Hitler did not have Jewish ancestry through his father.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] "If that was the case, we wouldn't have got the DNA match with him," King said.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Adolf Hitler was born on 20 April 1889 in Braunau am Inn, a town in Austria-Hungary (present-day Austria), close to the border with Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He was the fourth of six children born to Alois Hitler and his third wife, Klara Pölzl.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Three of Hitler's siblings—Gustav, Ida, and Otto—died in infancy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Also living in the household were Alois's children from his second marriage: Alois Jr.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1892, the family moved to Passau, Germany, following Alois's promotion to the customs administration in Passau.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was promoted and transferred to Linz, Austria, on 1 April 1893, but the rest of the family remained in Passau.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] There, Hitler acquired the distinctive lower Bavarian dialect, rather than Austrian German, which marked his speech throughout his life.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The family returned to Austria and settled in Leonding on 9 May 1894, and in June 1895, Alois retired to Hafeld, near Lambach, where he farmed and kept bees.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler attended *Volksschule* (a state-funded primary school) in nearby Fischlham.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The move to Hafeld coincided with the onset of intense father–son conflicts caused by six-year-old Hitler's refusal to conform to the strict discipline of his school.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois tried to browbeat his son into obedience, while Adolf did his best to be the opposite of whatever his father wanted.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois would also beat his son, although his mother tried to protect him from regular beatings.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois Hitler's farming efforts at Hafeld were unsuccessful, and in 1897, the family moved to Lambach.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The eight-year-old Hitler took singing lessons, sang in the church choir, and even considered becoming a priest.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1898, the family returned permanently to Leonding.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was deeply affected by the death of his younger brother Edmund in 1900 from measles.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler transformed from a confident, outgoing, and conscientious student to a morose, detached boy who frequently clashed with his father and teachers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Paula Hitler recalled that Adolf was a teenage bully who would often slap her.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois had made a successful career in the customs bureau and wanted his son to follow in his footsteps.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later dramatised an episode from this period when his father took him to visit a customs office, depicting it as an event that gave rise to an unforgiving antagonism between father and son, who were both strong-willed.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Ignoring his son's desire to attend a classical high school and become an artist, Alois sent Hitler to the *Realschule* in Linz in September 1900.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler rebelled against this decision, and in *Mein Kampf* states that he intentionally performed poorly in school, hoping that once his father saw "what little progress I was making at the technical school he would let me devote myself to my dream".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Like many Austrian Germans, Hitler began to develop German nationalist ideas from a young age.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He expressed loyalty only to Germany, despising the declining Habsburg monarchy and its rule over an ethnically diverse empire.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and his friends used the greeting "Heil", and sang the "Deutschlandlied" instead of the Austrian Imperial anthem.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] After Alois's sudden death on 3 January 1903, Hitler's performance at school deteriorated, and his mother allowed him to leave.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He enrolled at the *Realschule* in Steyr in September 1904, where his behaviour and performance improved.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1905, after passing a repeat of the final exam, Hitler left the school without any ambitions for further education or clear plans for a career.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1907, Hitler left Linz to live and study fine art in Vienna, financed by an orphan's benefits and support from his mother.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He applied for admission to the Academy of Fine Arts Vienna but was rejected twice.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The director suggested Hitler should apply to the School of Architecture, but he lacked the necessary academic credentials because he had not finished secondary school.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 December 1907, his mother died of breast cancer at the age of 47; Hitler was 18 at the time.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1909, Hitler ran out of money and was forced to live a bohemian life in homeless shelters and the Meldemannstraße dormitory.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He earned money as a casual labourer and by painting and selling watercolours of Vienna's sights.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] During his time in Vienna, he pursued a growing passion for architecture and music, attending ten performances of *Lohengrin*, his favourite of Richard Wagner's operas.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In Vienna, Hitler was first exposed to racist rhetoric.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Populists such as mayor Karl Lueger exploited the city's prevalent antisemitic sentiment, occasionally also espousing German nationalist notions for political benefit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] German nationalism was especially widespread in the Mariahilf district, where Hitler then lived.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Georg Ritter von Schönerer became a major influence on Hitler, and he developed an admiration for Martin Luther.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler read newspapers and pamphlets that promoted prejudice and warned of an influx of Eastern European Jews, as well as writings by figures such as Houston Stewart Chamberlain, Charles Darwin, Friedrich Nietzsche, Gustave Le Bon, and Arthur Schopenhauer.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] During his years in Vienna he also developed strong anti-Slavic sentiments.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The origin and development of Hitler's antisemitism remain a matter of debate.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] His friend August Kubizek claimed that Hitler was a "confirmed antisemite" before he left Linz.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] However, the historian Brigitte Hamann describes Kubizek's claim as "problematical".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler states in *Mein Kampf* that he first became an antisemite in Vienna, Reinhold Hanisch, who helped him to sell his paintings, disagrees.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sold some of his art through a Jewish businessman named Samuel Morgenstern while living in Vienna.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of Morgenstern's clients were Jewish; for example, a lawyer named Josef Feingold purchased several of Hitler's paintings of Vienna's historical architecture.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Evans states that "historians now generally agree that his notorious, murderous antisemitism emerged well after Germany's defeat in World War I, as a product of the paranoid "stab-in-the-back" explanation for the catastrophe".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler received the final part of his father's estate in May 1913 and moved to Munich.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] When he was conscripted into the Austro-Hungarian Army, he journeyed to Salzburg on 5 February 1914 for medical assessment.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] After he was deemed unfit for service, he returned to Munich.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later claimed that he did not wish to serve the Habsburg Empire because of the mixture of races in its army and his belief that the collapse of Austria-Hungary was imminent.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Hitler was living in Munich and voluntarily enlisted in the Bavarian Army.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] According to a 1924 report by the Bavarian authorities, allowing Hitler to serve was most likely an administrative error, because as an Austrian citizen, he should have been returned to Austria.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Posted to the Bavarian Reserve Infantry Regiment 16 (1st Company of the List Regiment), he served as a dispatch runner on the Western Front in France and Belgium, spending nearly half his time at the regimental headquarters in Fournes-en-Weppes, well behind the front lines.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1914, he was present at the First Battle of Ypres and in that year was decorated for bravery, receiving the Iron Cross, Second Class.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] During the war, he was saved by his commanding officer, Fritz Wiedemann, who pulled Hitler out of the rubble of a collapsed building while under heavy fire.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] During his service at headquarters, Hitler pursued his artistic interests, drawing cartoons and providing instructions for an army newspaper.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] During the Battle of the Somme in October 1916, he was wounded in the left thigh when a shell exploded in the dispatch runners' dugout.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler spent almost two months recovering in hospital at Beelitz, returning to his regiment on 5 March 1917.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He was present at the Battle of Arras of 1917 and the Battle of Passchendaele.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He received the black Wound Badge on 18 May 1918.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Three months later, in August 1918, on a recommendation by Lieutenant Hugo Gutmann, his Jewish superior, Hitler received the Iron Cross, First Class, a decoration rarely awarded at Hitler's *Gefreiter* rank.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 15 October 1918, he was temporarily blinded in a mustard gas attack and was hospitalised in Pasewalk.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, Hitler learned of Germany's defeat, and, by his own account, suffered a second bout of blindness after receiving this news.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler described his role in World War I as "the greatest of all experiences" and was praised by his commanding officers for his bravery.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] His wartime experience reinforced his German patriotism, and he was shocked by Germany's capitulation in November 1918.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] His displeasure with the collapse of the war effort began to shape his ideology.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Treaty of Versailles stipulated that Germany had to relinquish several of its territories and demilitarise the Rhineland.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The treaty imposed economic sanctions and levied heavy reparations on the country.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Many Germans saw the treaty as an unjust humiliation.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] They especially objected to Article 231, which they interpreted as declaring Germany responsible for the war.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Versailles Treaty and the economic, social, and political conditions in Germany after the war were later exploited by Hitler for political gain.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] After the war, Hitler returned to Munich.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Without formal education or career prospects, he remained in the army.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In July 1919, he was appointed *Verbindungsmann* (intelligence agent) of an *Aufklärungskommando* (reconnaissance unit) of the *Reichswehr*, assigned to influence other soldiers and to infiltrate the German Workers' Party (DAP).
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] At a DAP meeting on 12 September 1919, Party chairman Anton Drexler was impressed by Hitler's oratorical skills.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He gave him a copy of his pamphlet *My Political Awakening*, which contained antisemitic, nationalist, anti-capitalist, and anti-Marxist ideas.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On the orders of his army superiors, Hitler applied to join the party, and within a week was accepted as party member 555 (the party began counting membership at 500 to give the impression they were a much larger party).
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made his earliest known written statement about the Jewish question in a 16 September 1919 letter to Adolf Gemlich (now known as the Gemlich letter).
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In the letter, Hitler argues that the aim of the government "must unshakably be the removal of the Jews altogether".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] At the DAP, Hitler met Dietrich Eckart, one of the party's founders and a member of the occult Thule Society.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Eckart became Hitler's mentor, exchanging ideas with him and introducing him to a wide range of Munich society.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] To increase its appeal, the DAP changed its name to the *Nationalsozialistische Deutsche Arbeiterpartei* (National Socialist German Workers' Party (NSDAP), now known as the "Nazi Party").
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler designed the party's banner of a swastika in a white circle on a red background.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was discharged from the army on 31 March 1920, and began working full-time for the party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The party headquarters was in Munich, a centre for anti-government German nationalists determined to eliminate Marxism and undermine the Weimar Republic.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In February 1921, already highly effective at crowd manipulation, Hitler spoke to a crowd of over 6,000.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] To publicise the meeting, two truckloads of party supporters drove around Munich waving swastika flags and distributing leaflets.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler soon gained notoriety for his rowdy polemic speeches against the Treaty of Versailles, rival politicians, and especially against Marxists and Jews.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In June 1921, while Hitler and Eckart were on a fundraising trip to Berlin, a mutiny broke out within the Nazi Party in Munich.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Members of its executive committee wanted to merge with the Nuremberg-based German Socialist Party (DSP).
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler returned to Munich on 11 July and angrily tendered his resignation.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee members realised that the resignation of their leading public figure and speaker would mean the end of the party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler announced he would rejoin on the condition that he would replace Drexler as party chairman, and that the party headquarters would remain in Munich.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee agreed, and he rejoined the party on 26 July as member 3,680.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler continued to face some opposition within the Nazi Party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Opponents of Hitler in the leadership had Hermann Esser expelled from the party, and they printed 3,000 copies of a pamphlet attacking Hitler as a traitor to the party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In the following days, Hitler spoke to several large audiences and defended himself and Esser, to thunderous applause.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] His strategy proved successful, and at a special party congress on 29 July, he was granted absolute power as party chairman, succeeding Drexler, by a vote of 533 to 1.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's vitriolic beer hall speeches began attracting regular audiences.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] A demagogue, he became adept at using populist themes, including the use of scapegoats, who were blamed for his listeners' economic hardships.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used personal magnetism and an understanding of crowd psychology to his advantage while engaged in public speaking.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Historians have noted the hypnotic effect of his rhetoric on large audiences, and of his eyes in small groups.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Early followers included Rudolf Hess, the former air force ace Hermann Göring, and the army captain Ernst Röhm.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Röhm became head of the Nazis' paramilitary organisation, the *Sturmabteilung* (SA, "Stormtroopers"), which protected meetings and attacked political opponents.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] A critical influence on Hitler's thinking during this period was the *Aufbau Vereinigung*, a conspiratorial group of White Russian exiles and early Nazis.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The group, financed with funds channelled from wealthy industrialists, introduced Hitler to the idea of a Jewish conspiracy, linking international finance with Bolshevism.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The programme of the Nazi Party was laid out in their 25-point programme on 24 February 1920.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] This did not represent a coherent ideology, but was a conglomeration of received ideas which had currency in the *völkisch* pan-Germanic movement, such as ultranationalism, opposition to the Treaty of Versailles, distrust of capitalism, as well as some socialist ideas.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] For Hitler, the most important aspect of it was its strong antisemitic stance.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He also perceived the programme as primarily a basis for propaganda and for attracting people to the party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, Hitler enlisted the help of World War I General Erich Ludendorff for an attempted coup known as the Beer Hall Putsch.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party used Italian Fascism as a model for their appearance and policies.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler wanted to emulate Benito Mussolini's March on Rome in 1922 by staging his own coup in Bavaria, to be followed by a challenge to the government in Berlin.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and Ludendorff sought the support of *Staatskommissar* (State Commissioner) Gustav Ritter von Kahr, Bavaria's *de facto* ruler.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] However, Kahr, along with Police Chief Hans Ritter von Seisser and Reichswehr General Otto von Lossow, wanted to install a nationalist dictatorship without Hitler.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 8 November 1923, Hitler and the SA stormed a public meeting of 3,000 people organised by Kahr in the Bürgerbräukeller, a beer hall in Munich.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Interrupting Kahr's speech, he announced that the national revolution had begun and declared the formation of a new government with Ludendorff.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Retiring to a back room, Hitler, with his pistol drawn, demanded and subsequently received the support of Kahr, Seisser, and Lossow.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's forces initially succeeded in occupying the local Reichswehr and police headquarters, but Kahr and his cohorts quickly withdrew their support.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Neither the Army nor the state police joined forces with Hitler.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The next day, Hitler and his followers marched from the beer hall to the Bavarian War Ministry to overthrow the Bavarian government, but police dispersed them.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In the failed coup, 16 Nazi Party members and four police officers were killed.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler fled to the home of Ernst Hanfstaengl and by some accounts contemplated suicide.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He was depressed but calm when arrested on 11 November 1923 for high treason.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] His trial before the special People's Court in Munich began in February 1924, and Alfred Rosenberg became the temporary leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 April, Hitler was sentenced to five years' *Festungshaft* ('fortress confinement') at Landsberg Prison.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] There, he received friendly treatment from the guards and was allowed mail from supporters and regular visits by party comrades.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Pardoned by the Bavarian Supreme Court, he was released from jail on 20 December 1924, against the state prosecutor's objections.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Including time on remand, Hitler served just over one year in prison.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] While at Landsberg, Hitler dictated most of the first volume of *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] 'My Struggle'; originally titled *Four and a Half Years of Struggle against Lies, Stupidity, and Cowardice*) at first to his chauffeur, Emil Maurice, and then to his deputy, Rudolf Hess.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The book, dedicated to Thule Society member Dietrich Eckart, was an autobiography and exposition of his ideology.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The book laid out Hitler's plans for territorial expansion as well as transforming German society into a dictatorship based on race.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Throughout the book, Jews are equated with "germs" and presented as the "international poisoners" of society.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] According to Hitler's ideology, the only solution was their extermination.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler did not describe exactly how this was to be accomplished, his "inherent genocidal thrust is undeniable", according to Ian Kershaw.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Published in two volumes in 1925 and 1926, *Mein Kampf* sold 228,000 copies between 1925 and 1932.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] One million copies were sold in 1933, Hitler's first year in office.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly before Hitler was eligible for parole, the Bavarian government attempted to have him deported to Austria.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Austrian federal chancellor rejected the request on the specious grounds that his service in the German Army made his Austrian citizenship void.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler formally renounced his Austrian citizenship on 7 April 1925.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] At the time of Hitler's release from prison, politics in Germany had become less combative, and the economy had improved, limiting Hitler's opportunities for political agitation.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] As a result of the failed Beer Hall Putsch, the Nazi Party and its affiliated organisations were banned in Bavaria.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with the prime minister of Bavaria, Heinrich Held, on 4 January 1925, Hitler agreed to respect the state's authority and promised that he would seek political power only through the democratic process.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The meeting paved the way for the ban on the Nazi Party to be lifted on 16 February.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] However, after an inflammatory speech he gave on 27 February, Hitler was barred from public speaking by the Bavarian authorities, a ban that remained in place until 1927.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] To advance his political ambitions despite the ban, Hitler appointed Gregor Strasser, Otto Strasser, and Joseph Goebbels to organise and enlarge the Nazi Party in northern Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Gregor Strasser steered a more independent political course, emphasising the socialist elements of the party's programme.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The stock market in the United States crashed on 24 October 1929.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The impact in Germany was dire: millions became unemployed, and several major banks collapsed.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazi Party prepared to take advantage of the emergency to gain support for their party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] They promised to repudiate the Versailles Treaty, strengthen the economy, and provide jobs.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Great Depression provided a political opportunity for Hitler.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Germans were ambivalent about the parliamentary republic, which faced challenges from right- and left-wing extremists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The moderate political parties were increasingly unable to stem the tide of extremism, and the German referendum of 1929 helped to elevate Nazi ideology.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The elections of September 1930 resulted in the break-up of a grand coalition and its replacement with a minority cabinet.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Its leader, chancellor Heinrich Brüning of the Centre Party, governed through emergency decrees from President Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Governance by decree became the new norm, paving the way for authoritarian forms of government.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party rose from obscurity to win 18.3 per cent of the vote and 107 parliamentary seats in the 1930 election, becoming the second-largest party in parliament.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made a prominent appearance at the trial of two Reichswehr officers, Lieutenants Richard Scheringer and Hanns Ludin, in late 1930.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Both were charged with membership in the Nazi Party, at that time illegal for Reichswehr personnel.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The prosecution argued that the Nazi Party was extremist, prompting defence lawyer Hans Frank to call on Hitler to testify.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 September 1930, Hitler testified that his party would pursue political power solely through democratic elections, which won him many supporters in the officer corps.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Brüning's austerity measures brought little economic improvement and were extremely unpopular.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler exploited this by targeting his political messages specifically at people who had been affected by the inflation of the 1920s and the Depression, such as farmers, war veterans, and the middle class.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Although Hitler had terminated his Austrian citizenship in 1925, he did not acquire German citizenship for almost seven years.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] This meant that he was stateless, legally unable to run for public office, and still faced the risk of deportation.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 February 1932, the interior minister of Brunswick, Dietrich Klagges, who was a member of the Nazi Party, appointed Hitler as administrator for the state's delegation to the Reichsrat in Berlin, making Hitler a citizen of Brunswick, and thus of Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler ran against Hindenburg in the 1932 presidential election.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] A speech to the Industry Club in Düsseldorf on 27 January 1932 won him support from many of Germany's most powerful industrialists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg had support from various nationalist, monarchist, Catholic, and republican parties, and some Social Democrats.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used the campaign slogan "*Hitler über Deutschland*" ("Hitler over Germany"), a reference to his political ambitions and his campaigning by aircraft.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He was one of the first politicians to use aircraft travel for campaigning and used it effectively.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler came in second in both rounds of the election, garnering more than 35 per cent of the vote in the final election.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Although he lost to Hindenburg, this election established Hitler as a strong force in German politics.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The absence of an effective government prompted two influential politicians, Franz von Papen and Alfred Hugenberg, along with several other industrialists and businessmen, to write a letter to Hindenburg.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The signers urged Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as leader of a government "independent from parliamentary parties", which could turn into a movement that would "enrapture millions of people".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg reluctantly agreed to appoint Hitler as chancellor after two further parliamentary elections—in July and November 1932—had not resulted in the formation of a majority government.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler headed a short-lived coalition government formed by the Nazi Party (which had the most seats in the Reichstag) and Hugenberg's party, the German National People's Party (DNVP).
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 30 January 1933, the new cabinet was sworn in during a brief ceremony in Hindenburg's office.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party gained three posts: Hitler was named chancellor, Wilhelm Frick Minister of the Interior, and Hermann Göring Minister of the Interior for Prussia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler had insisted on the ministerial positions as a way to gain control over the police in much of Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] As chancellor, Hitler worked against attempts by the Nazi Party's opponents to build a majority government.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Because of the political stalemate, he asked Hindenburg to again dissolve the Reichstag, and elections were scheduled for early March.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 27 February 1933, the Reichstag building was set on fire.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Göring blamed a communist plot, as the Dutch communist Marinus van der Lubbe was found in incriminating circumstances inside the burning building.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Until the 1960s, some historians, including William L.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Shirer and Alan Bullock, thought the Nazi Party was responsible; now the view of most historians is van der Lubbe started the fire alone.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] At Hitler's urging, Hindenburg responded by signing the Reichstag Fire Decree of 28 February, drafted by the Nazis, which suspended basic rights and allowed detention without trial.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The decree was permitted under Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution, which gave the president the power to take emergency measures to protect public safety and order.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Activities of the German Communist Party (KPD) were suppressed, and 4,000 KPD members were arrested.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition to political campaigning, the Nazi Party engaged in paramilitary violence and the spread of anti-communist propaganda, in the days preceding the election.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On election day, 6 March 1933, the Nazis’ share of the vote increased to 44%, and the party acquired the largest number of seats in parliament.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's party failed to secure an absolute majority, necessitating another coalition with the DNVP.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 March 1933, the new *Reichstag* was constituted with an opening ceremony at the Garrison Church in Potsdam.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] This "Day of Potsdam" was held to demonstrate unity between the Nazi movement and the old Prussian elite and military.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler appeared in a morning coat and humbly greeted Hindenburg.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] To achieve full political control despite not having an absolute majority in parliament, Hitler's government brought the *Ermächtigungsgesetz* (Enabling Act) to a vote in the newly elected *Reichstag*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act—officially titled the *Gesetz zur Behebung der Not von Volk und Reich* ("Law to Remedy the Distress of People and Reich")—gave Hitler's cabinet the power to enact laws without the consent of the Reichstag for four years.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] These laws could (with certain exceptions) deviate from the constitution.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Since it would affect the constitution, the Enabling Act required a two-thirds majority to pass.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Leaving nothing to chance, the Nazis used the provisions of the Reichstag Fire Decree to arrest all 81 Communist deputies (in spite of their virulent campaign against the party, the Nazis had allowed the KPD to contest the election) and prevent several Social Democrats from attending.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 23 March 1933, the *Reichstag* assembled at the Kroll Opera House under turbulent circumstances.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Ranks of SA men served as guards inside the building, while large groups outside, opposing the proposed legislation, shouted slogans and threats towards the arriving members of parliament.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] After Hitler verbally promised Centre party leader Ludwig Kaas that Hindenburg would retain his power of veto, Kaas announced the Centre Party would support the Enabling Act.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act was passed by a vote of 444–94, with all parties except the Social Democrats voting in favour.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Enabling Act, along with the Reichstag Fire Decree, transformed Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Having achieved full control over the legislative and executive branches of government, Hitler and his allies began to suppress the remaining opposition.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Social Democratic Party was made illegal, and its assets were seized.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] While many trade union delegates were in Berlin for May Day activities, SA stormtroopers occupied union offices around the country.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 2 May 1933, all trade unions were forced to dissolve, and their leaders were arrested.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The German Labour Front was formed as an umbrella organisation to represent all workers, administrators, and company owners, thus reflecting the concept of Nazism in the spirit of Hitler's *Volksgemeinschaft* ("people's community").
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of June, the other parties had been intimidated into disbanding.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] This included the Nazis' nominal coalition partner, the DNVP; with the SA's help, Hitler forced its leader, Hugenberg, to resign on 29 June.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 14 July 1933, the Nazi Party was declared the only legal political party in Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The demands of the SA for more political and military power caused anxiety among military, industrial, and political leaders.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler purged the entire SA leadership in the Night of the Long Knives, which took place from 30 June to 2 July 1934.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler targeted Ernst Röhm and other SA leaders who, along with several Hitler's political adversaries (such as Gregor Strasser and former chancellor Kurt von Schleicher), were rounded up, arrested, and shot.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] While the international community and some Germans were shocked by the killings, many in Germany believed Hitler was restoring order.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On the previous day, the cabinet had enacted the Law Concerning the Head of State of the German Reich.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] This law stated that upon Hindenburg's death, the office of president would be abolished, and its powers merged with those of the chancellor.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler thus became head of state as well as head of government and was formally named as *Führer und Reichskanzler* (Leader and Chancellor of the Reich), although *Reichskanzler* was eventually dropped.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] With this action, Hitler eliminated the last legal remedy by which he could be removed from office.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] As head of state, Hitler became commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 19 August, the merger of the presidency with the chancellorship was approved by 88 per cent of the electorate voting in a plebiscite.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, Hitler used blackmail to consolidate his hold over the military by instigating the Blomberg–Fritsch affair.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler forced his War Minister, Field Marshal Werner von Blomberg, to resign by using a police dossier that showed that Blomberg's new wife had a record for prostitution.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Army commander Colonel-General Werner von Fritsch was removed after the *Schutzstaffel* (SS) produced allegations that he had engaged in a homosexual relationship.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Both men had fallen into disfavour because they objected to Hitler's demand to make the *Wehrmacht* ready for war as early as 1938.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler assumed Blomberg's title of Commander-in-Chief, thus taking personal command of the armed forces.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He replaced the Ministry of War with the *Oberkommando der Wehrmacht* (OKW), headed by General Wilhelm Keitel.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On the same day, 16 generals were stripped of their commands, and 44 more were transferred; all were suspected of not being sufficiently pro-Nazi.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] By early February 1938, 12 more generals had been removed.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler took care to give his dictatorship the appearance of legality.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of his decrees were explicitly based on the Reichstag Fire Decree and hence on Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The *Reichstag* renewed the Enabling Act twice, each time for four years.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] While elections to the *Reichstag* were still held (in 1933, 1936, and 1938), voters were presented with a single list of Nazis and pro-Nazi "guests" which received well over 90 per cent of the vote.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] These sham elections were held in far-from-secret conditions; the Nazis threatened severe reprisals against anyone who did not vote or who voted against.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1934, Hitler appointed *Reichsbank* President Hjalmar Schacht as Minister of Economics, and in the following year, as Plenipotentiary for War Economy in charge of preparing the economy for war.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Reconstruction and rearmament were financed through Mefo bills, printing money, and seizing the assets of people arrested as enemies of the state, including Jews.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of unemployed fell from six million in 1932 to fewer than one million in 1936.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler oversaw one of the largest infrastructure improvement campaigns in German history, leading to the construction of dams, *autobahns*, railroads, and other civil works.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Wages were slightly lower in the mid- to late 1930s compared with wages during the Weimar Republic, while the cost of living increased by 25 per cent.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The average workweek increased during the shift to a war economy; by 1939, the average German was working between 47 and 50 hours a week.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's government sponsored architecture on an immense scale.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Albert Speer, instrumental in implementing Hitler's classicist reinterpretation of German culture, was placed in charge of the proposed architectural renovations of Berlin.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Despite a threatened multi-nation boycott, Germany hosted the 1936 Olympic Games.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler officiated at the opening ceremonies and attended events at both the Winter Games in Garmisch-Partenkirchen and the Summer Games in Berlin.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with German military leaders on 3 February 1933, Hitler spoke of "conquest for *Lebensraum* in the East and its ruthless Germanisation" as his ultimate foreign policy objectives.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler found Bülow's goals to be too modest.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In speeches during this period, he stressed what he termed the peaceful goals of his policies and a willingness to work within international agreements.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] At the first meeting of his cabinet in 1933, Hitler prioritised military spending over unemployment relief.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany withdrew from the League of Nations and the World Disarmament Conference in October 1933.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In January 1935, over 90 per cent of the people of the Saarland, then under League of Nations administration, voted to unite with Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] That March, Hitler announced an expansion of the Wehrmacht to 600,000 members—six times the number permitted by the Versailles Treaty—including development of an air force (*Luftwaffe*) and an increase in the size of the navy (*Kriegsmarine*).
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, France, Italy, and the League of Nations condemned these violations of the Treaty but did nothing to stop them.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The Anglo-German Naval Agreement (AGNA) of 18 June allowed German tonnage to increase to 35 per cent of that of the Royal Navy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler called the signing of the AGNA "the happiest day of his life", believing that the agreement marked the beginning of the Anglo-German alliance he had predicted in *Mein Kampf*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] France and Italy were not consulted before the signing, directly undermining the League of Nations and setting the Treaty of Versailles on the path towards irrelevance.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany reoccupied the demilitarised zone in the Rhineland in March 1936, in violation of the Versailles Treaty.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sent troops to Spain to support Francisco Franco and his Nationalist faction during the Spanish Civil War after receiving an appeal for help in July 1936.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] At the same time, Hitler continued his efforts to create an Anglo-German alliance.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1936, in response to a growing economic crisis caused by his rearmament efforts, Hitler ordered Göring to implement a Four Year Plan to prepare Germany for war within the next four years.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] The plan envisaged an all-out struggle between "Judaeo-Bolshevism" and German Nazism, which in Hitler's view required a committed effort of rearmament regardless of the economic costs.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In October 1936, Count Galeazzo Ciano, foreign minister of Mussolini's government, visited Germany, where he signed a Nine-Point Protocol as an expression of *rapprochement* and had a personal meeting with Hitler.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 November, Mussolini declared an "axis" between Germany and Italy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 November, Germany signed the Anti-Comintern Pact with Japan.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, China, Italy, and Poland were also invited to join the Anti-Comintern Pact, but only Italy signed in 1937.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler abandoned his plan of an Anglo-German alliance, blaming "inadequate" British leadership.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] At a meeting in the Reich Chancellery with his foreign ministers and military chiefs that November, Hitler restated his intention of acquiring *Lebensraum* for the German people.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He ordered preparations for war in the East to begin as early as 1938 and no later than 1943.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In the event of his death, the conference minutes, recorded as the Hossbach Memorandum, were to be regarded as his "political testament".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] He felt that a severe decline in living standards in Germany as a result of the economic crisis could only be stopped by military aggression aimed at seizing Austria and Czechoslovakia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler urged quick action before Britain and France gained a permanent lead in the arms race.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, in the wake of the Blomberg–Fritsch affair, Hitler asserted control of the military-foreign policy apparatus, dismissing Neurath as foreign minister and appointing himself as War Minister.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p01] From early 1938 onwards, Hitler was carrying out a foreign policy ultimately aimed at war.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In February 1938, on the advice of his newly appointed foreign minister, the strongly pro-Japanese Joachim von Ribbentrop, Hitler ended the Sino-German alliance with the Republic of China to instead enter into an alliance with the more modern and powerful Empire of Japan.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler announced German recognition of Manchukuo, the Japanese puppet state in Manchuria, and renounced German claims to their former colonies in the Pacific held by Japan.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered an end to arms shipments to China and recalled all German officers working with the Chinese Army.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In retaliation, Chinese General Chiang Kai-shek cancelled all Sino-German economic agreements, depriving the Germans of many Chinese raw materials.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 March 1938, Hitler announced the unification of Austria with Germany in the *Anschluss*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler then turned his attention to the ethnic German population of the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28–29 March 1938, Hitler held a series of secret meetings in Berlin with Konrad Henlein of the Sudeten German Party, the largest of the ethnic German parties of the Sudetenland.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The men agreed that Henlein would demand increased autonomy for Sudeten Germans from the Czechoslovak government, thus providing a pretext for German military action against Czechoslovakia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In April 1938, Henlein told the foreign minister of Hungary that "whatever the Czech government might offer, he would always raise still higher demands ... he wanted to sabotage an understanding by any means because this was the only method to blow up Czechoslovakia quickly".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In private, Hitler considered the Sudeten issue unimportant; his real intention was a war of conquest against Czechoslovakia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler ordered the OKW to prepare for *Fall Grün* (Case Green), the code name for an invasion of Czechoslovakia.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of intense French and British diplomatic pressure, on 5 September, Czechoslovak president Edvard Beneš unveiled the "Fourth Plan" for constitutional reorganisation of his country, which agreed to most of Henlein's demands for Sudeten autonomy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Henlein's party responded to Beneš's offer by instigating a series of violent clashes with the Czechoslovak police that led to the declaration of martial law in certain Sudeten districts.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany was dependent on imported oil; a confrontation with Britain over the Czechoslovak dispute could curtail Germany's oil supplies.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] This forced Hitler to call off *Fall Grün*, originally planned for 1 October 1938.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 29 September, Hitler, Neville Chamberlain, Édouard Daladier, and Mussolini attended a one-day conference in Munich that led to the Munich Agreement, which handed over the Sudetenland districts to Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Chamberlain was satisfied with the Munich conference, calling the outcome "peace for our time", while Hitler was angered about the missed opportunity for war in 1938; he expressed his disappointment in a speech on 9 October in Saarbrücken.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In Hitler's view, the British-brokered peace, although favourable to the ostensible German demands, was a diplomatic defeat which spurred his intent of limiting British power to pave the way for the eastern expansion of Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of the summit, Hitler was selected *Time* magazine's Man of the Year for 1938.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1938 and early 1939, the continuing economic crisis caused by rearmament forced Hitler to make major defence cuts.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In his "Export or die" speech of 30 January 1939, he called for an economic offensive to increase German foreign exchange holdings to pay for raw materials such as high-grade iron needed for military weapons.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 14 March 1939, under threat from Hungary, Slovakia declared independence and received protection from Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The next day, in violation of the Munich Agreement and possibly as a result of the deepening economic crisis requiring additional assets, Hitler ordered the Wehrmacht to invade the Czech rump state, and from Prague Castle he proclaimed the territory a German protectorate.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In private discussions in 1939, Hitler declared Britain the main enemy to be defeated and that Poland's obliteration was a necessary prelude for that goal.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The eastern flank would be secured, and land would be added to Germany's *Lebensraum*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Offended by the British "guarantee" on 31 March 1939 of Polish independence, he said, "I shall brew them a devil's drink".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In a speech in Wilhelmshaven for the launch of the battleship *Tirpitz* on 1 April, he threatened to denounce the Anglo-German Naval Agreement if the British continued to guarantee Polish independence, which he perceived as an "encirclement" policy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Poland was to either become a German satellite state, or it would be neutralised to secure the Reich's eastern flank and prevent a possible British blockade.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler initially favoured the idea of a satellite state, but upon its rejection by the Polish government, he decided to invade and made this the main foreign policy goal of 1939.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 3 April, Hitler ordered the military to prepare for *Fall Weiss* ("Case White"), the plan for invading Poland on 25 August.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In a Reichstag speech on 28 April, he renounced both the Anglo-German Naval Agreement and the German–Polish Non-Aggression Pact.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians such as William Carr, Gerhard Weinberg, and Ian Kershaw have argued that one reason for Hitler's rush to war was his fear of an early death.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He had repeatedly claimed that he must lead Germany into war before he got too old, as his successors might lack his strength of will.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was concerned that a military attack against Poland could result in a premature war with Britain.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's foreign minister and former Ambassador to London, Joachim von Ribbentrop, assured him that neither Britain nor France would honour its commitments to Poland.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Accordingly, on 22 August 1939, Hitler ordered a military mobilisation against Poland.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] This plan required tacit Soviet support, and the non-aggression pact (the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact) between Germany and the Soviet Union, led by Joseph Stalin, included a secret agreement to partition Poland between the two countries.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Contrary to Ribbentrop's prediction that Britain would sever Anglo-Polish ties, Britain and Poland signed the Anglo-Polish alliance on 25 August 1939.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] This, along with news from Italy that Mussolini would not honour the Pact of Steel, prompted Hitler to postpone the attack on Poland from 25 August to 1 September.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler unsuccessfully tried to manoeuvre the British into neutrality by offering them a non-aggression guarantee on 25 August; he then instructed Ribbentrop to present a last-minute peace plan with an impossibly short time limit in an effort to blame the imminent war on British and Polish inaction.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 1 September 1939, Germany invaded western Poland under the pretext of having been denied claims to the Free City of Danzig and the right to extraterritorial roads across the Polish Corridor, which Germany had ceded under the Versailles Treaty.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In response, Britain and France declared war on Germany on 3 September, surprising Hitler and prompting him to angrily ask Ribbentrop, "Now what?" Britain and France did not act on their declarations immediately, and on 17 September, Soviet forces invaded eastern Poland.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The fall of Poland was followed by what contemporary journalists dubbed the "Phoney War" or *Sitzkrieg* ("sitting war").
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler instructed the two newly appointed Gauleiters of north-western Poland, Albert Forster of Reichsgau Danzig-West Prussia and Arthur Greiser of Reichsgau Wartheland, to Germanise their areas, with "no questions asked" about how this was accomplished.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In Forster's area, ethnic Poles merely had to sign forms stating that they had German blood.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In contrast, Greiser agreed with Himmler and carried out an ethnic cleansing campaign towards Poles.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Greiser soon complained that Forster was allowing thousands of Poles to be accepted as "racial" Germans and thus endangered German "racial purity".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] This inaction has been cited as an example of the theory of "working towards the Führer", in which Hitler issued vague instructions and expected his subordinates to develop policies independently.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Another dispute pitched one side represented by Heinrich Himmler and Greiser, who championed ethnic cleansing in Poland, against another represented by Göring and Hans Frank (governor-general of occupied Poland), who called for turning Poland into the "granary" of the Reich.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 February 1940, the dispute was initially settled in favour of the Göring–Frank view, which ended the economically disruptive mass expulsions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 May 1940, Himmler issued a memo entitled "Some Thoughts on the Treatment of Alien Population in the East", calling for the expulsion of the entire Jewish population of Europe into Africa and the reduction of the Polish population to a "leaderless class of labourers".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler called Himmler's memo "good and correct", and, ignoring Göring and Frank, implemented the Himmler–Greiser policy in Poland.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 9 April, German forces invaded Denmark and Norway.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On the same day, Hitler proclaimed the birth of the Greater Germanic Reich, his vision of a united empire of Germanic nations of Europe in which the Dutch, Flemish, and Scandinavians were joined into a "racially pure" polity under German leadership.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In May 1940, Germany attacked France, and conquered Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] These victories prompted Mussolini to have Italy join forces with Hitler on 10 June.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] France and Germany signed an armistice on 22 June.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw notes that Hitler's popularity within Germany—and German support for the war—reached its peak when he returned to Berlin on 6 July from his tour of Paris.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the unexpected swift victory, Hitler promoted 12 generals to the rank of field marshal during the 1940 Field Marshal Ceremony.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Britain, whose troops were forced to evacuate France by sea from Dunkirk, continued to fight alongside other British dominions in the Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler made peace overtures to the new British prime minister, Winston Churchill, and upon their rejection, he ordered a series of aerial attacks on Royal Air Force airbases and radar stations in southeast England.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 September, the systematic nightly bombing of London began.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The German Luftwaffe failed to defeat the Royal Air Force in what became known as the Battle of Britain.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] By the end of September, Hitler realised that air superiority for the invasion of Britain (in Operation Sea Lion) could not be achieved, and ordered the operation postponed.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The nightly air raids on British cities intensified and continued for months, including London, Plymouth, and Coventry.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 27 September 1940, the Tripartite Pact was signed in Berlin by Saburō Kurusu of Imperial Japan, Hitler, and Italian foreign minister Ciano, and later expanded to include Hungary, Romania, and Bulgaria, thus yielding the Axis powers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's attempt to integrate the Soviet Union into the anti-British bloc failed after inconclusive talks between Hitler and Molotov in Berlin in November, and he ordered preparations for the invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In early 1941, German forces were deployed to North Africa, the Balkans, and the Middle East.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In February, German forces arrived in Libya to bolster the Italian presence.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler launched the invasion of Yugoslavia, quickly followed by the invasion of Greece.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In May, German forces were sent to support Iraqi forces fighting against the British and to invade Crete.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 November, Hitler met in Berlin with Amin al-Husseini, the Grand Mufti of Jerusalem.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 June 1941, contravening the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact of 1939, over three million Axis troops attacked the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] This offensive (codenamed Operation Barbarossa) was intended to destroy the Soviet Union and seize its natural resources for subsequent aggression against the Western powers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The action was also part of the overall plan to obtain more living space for German people; and Hitler thought a successful invasion would force Britain to negotiate a surrender.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The invasion conquered a huge area, including the Baltic republics, Belarus, and West Ukraine.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] By early August, Axis troops had advanced 500 km (310 miles) and won the Battle of Smolensk.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Army Group Centre to temporarily halt its advance to Moscow and divert its Panzer groups to aid in the encirclement of Leningrad and Kiev.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] His generals disagreed with this change, having advanced within 400 km (250 miles) of Moscow, and his decision caused a crisis among the military leadership.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The pause provided the Red Army with an opportunity to mobilise fresh reserves; the historian Russel Stolfi considers it to be one of the major factors that caused the failure of the Moscow offensive, which was resumed in October 1941 and ended disastrously in December.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] During this crisis, Hitler appointed himself as head of the *Oberkommando des Heeres*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 December 1941, Japan attacked the American fleet based at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Four days later, Hitler declared war against the United States.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 18 December 1941, Himmler asked Hitler, "What to do with the Jews of Russia?", to which Hitler replied, *"als Partisanen auszurotten"* ("exterminate them as partisans").
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The Israeli historian Yehuda Bauer has commented that the remark is probably as close as historians will ever get to a definitive order from Hitler for the genocide carried out during the Holocaust.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1942, German forces were defeated in the Second Battle of El Alamein, thwarting Hitler's plans to seize the Suez Canal and the Middle East.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Overconfident in his own military expertise following the earlier victories in 1940, Hitler became distrustful of his Army High Command and began to interfere in military and tactical planning, with damaging consequences.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In December 1942 and January 1943, Hitler's repeated refusal to allow their withdrawal at the Battle of Stalingrad led to the near-destruction of the 6th Army.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Over 200,000 Axis soldiers were killed, and 235,000 were taken prisoner.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Thereafter came a decisive strategic defeat at the Battle of Kursk.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's military judgment became increasingly erratic, and Germany's military and economic position deteriorated, as did Hitler's health.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the Allied invasion of Sicily in 1943, Mussolini was removed from power by King Victor Emmanuel III after a vote of no confidence of the Grand Council of Fascism.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Marshal Pietro Badoglio, placed in charge of the government, soon surrendered to the Allies.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Throughout 1943 and 1944, the Soviet Union steadily forced Hitler's armies into retreat along the Eastern Front.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 6 June 1944, the Western Allied armies landed in northern France in one of the largest amphibious operations in history, Operation Overlord.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Many German officers concluded that defeat was inevitable and that continuing under Hitler's leadership would result in the complete destruction of the country.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Between 1939 and 1945, there were numerous plans to assassinate Hitler, some of which proceeded to significant degrees.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The most well-known and significant, the 20 July plot of 1944, came from within Germany and was at least partly driven by the increasing prospect of a German defeat in the war.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Part of Operation Valkyrie, the plot involved Claus von Stauffenberg planting a bomb in one of Hitler's headquarters, the Wolf's Lair at Rastenburg.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler narrowly survived because the staff officer Heinz Brandt moved the briefcase containing the bomb behind a leg of the heavy conference table, which deflected much of the blast.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Later, Hitler ordered reprisals, resulting in the execution of more than 4,900 people.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was put on the United Nations War Crimes Commission's first list of war criminals in December 1944, after determining that Hitler could be held criminally responsible for the acts of the Nazis in occupied countries.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] By March 1945, at least seven indictments had been filed against him.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] By late 1944, both the Red Army and the Western Allies were advancing into Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Recognising the strength and determination of the Red Army, Hitler decided to use his remaining mobile reserves against the American and British armies, which he perceived as far weaker.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 16 December, he launched the Ardennes Offensive to incite disunity among the Western Allies and perhaps convince them to join his fight against the Soviets.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] After some temporary successes, the offensive failed.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In any case only those who are inferior will remain after this struggle, for the good have already been killed".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The same day, Hitler ordered the destruction of all German industrial infrastructure before it could fall into Allied hands.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Minister for Armaments Albert Speer was entrusted with executing this scorched earth policy, but he secretly disobeyed the order.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's hope to negotiate peace with the United States and Britain was encouraged by the death of US president Franklin D.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Roosevelt on 12 April 1945, but contrary to his expectations, this caused no rift among the Allies.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 20 April, his 56th birthday, Hitler made his last trip from the *Führerbunker* to the surface.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In the ruined garden of the Reich Chancellery, he awarded Iron Crosses to boy soldiers of the Hitler Youth, who were now fighting the Red Army at the front near Berlin.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] By 21 April, Georgy Zhukov's 1st Belorussian Front had broken through the defences of General Gotthard Heinrici's Army Group Vistula during the Battle of the Seelow Heights and advanced to the outskirts of Berlin.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In denial about the dire situation, Hitler placed his hopes on the undermanned and under-equipped *Armeeabteilung Steiner* (Army Detachment Steiner), commanded by Felix Steiner.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Steiner to attack the northern flank of the salient, while the German Ninth Army was ordered to attack northward in a pincer attack.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] During a military conference on 22 April, Hitler enquired about Steiner's offensive.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He was informed that the attack had not been launched and that the Soviets had entered Berlin.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered everyone but Wilhelm Keitel, Alfred Jodl, Hans Krebs, and Wilhelm Burgdorf to leave the room, then launched into a tirade against the perceived treachery and incompetence of his generals, culminating in his declaration—for the first time—that "everything is lost".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He announced that he would stay in Berlin until the end and then shoot himself.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] By 23 April, the Red Army had surrounded Berlin, and Goebbels made a proclamation urging its citizens to defend the city.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] That same day, Göring sent a telegram from Berchtesgaden, arguing that as Hitler was isolated in Berlin, Göring should assume leadership of Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Göring set a deadline, after which he would consider Hitler incapacitated.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler responded by having Göring arrested, and in his last will and testament of 29 April, he removed Göring from all government positions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 April, Hitler discovered that Himmler, who had left Berlin on 20 April, was attempting to negotiate a surrender to the Western Allies.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He considered this treason and ordered Himmler's arrest.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He also ordered the execution of Hermann Fegelein, Himmler's SS representative at Hitler's headquarters in Berlin, for desertion.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] After midnight on the night of 28–29 April, Hitler married Eva Braun in a small civil ceremony in the *Führerbunker*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Later that afternoon, Hitler was informed that Mussolini had been executed by the Italian resistance movement on the previous day; this is believed to have increased his determination to avoid capture.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 30 April, Soviet troops were within five hundred metres of the Reich Chancellery when Hitler shot himself in the head and Braun bit into a cyanide capsule.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In accordance with Hitler's wishes, their corpses were carried outside to the garden behind the Reich Chancellery, where they were placed in a bomb crater, doused with petrol, and set on fire as the Red Army shelling continued.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Grand Admiral Karl Dönitz and Goebbels assumed Hitler's roles as head of state and chancellor respectively.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On the evening of 1 May, Goebbels and his wife, Magda, committed suicide in the Reich Chancellery garden, after having poisoned their six children with cyanide.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The remains of the Goebbels family, General Hans Krebs (who had committed suicide that day), and Hitler's dog Blondi were repeatedly buried and exhumed by the Soviets.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's and Braun's remains were alleged to have been moved as well, but this is most likely Soviet disinformation.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] There is no evidence that any identifiable remains of Hitler or Braun—with the exception of dental bridges—were ever found by them.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] While news of Hitler's death spread quickly, a death certificate was not issued until 1956, after a lengthy investigation to collect testimony from 42 witnesses.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's death was entered as an assumption of death based on this testimony.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The Holocaust and Germany's war in the East were based on Hitler's long-standing view that the Jews were the enemy of the German people, and that *Lebensraum* was needed for Germany's expansion.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He focused on Eastern Europe for this expansion, aiming to defeat Poland and the Soviet Union and then removing or killing the Jews and Slavs.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The *Generalplan Ost* (General Plan East) called for deporting the population of occupied Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union to West Siberia, for use as slave labour or to be murdered; the conquered territories were to be colonised by German or "Germanised" settlers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The goal was to implement this plan after the conquest of the Soviet Union, but when this failed, Hitler moved the plans forward.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] By January 1942, he had decided that the Jews, Slavs, and other deportees considered undesirable should be killed.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The genocide was organised and executed by Heinrich Himmler and Reinhard Heydrich.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The records of the Wannsee Conference, held on 20 January 1942 and led by Heydrich, with 15 senior Nazi officials participating, provide the clearest evidence of systematic planning for the Holocaust.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 February, Hitler was recorded saying, "we shall regain our health only by eliminating the Jews".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Similarly, at a meeting in July 1941 with leading functionaries of the Eastern territories, Hitler said that the easiest way to quickly pacify the areas would be best achieved by "shooting everyone who even looks odd".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Although no direct order from Hitler authorising the mass killings has surfaced, his public speeches, orders to his generals, and the diaries of Nazi officials demonstrate that he conceived and authorised the extermination of European Jewry.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] During the war, Hitler repeatedly stated his prophecy of 1939 was being fulfilled, namely, that a world war would bring about the annihilation of the Jewish race.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler approved the *Einsatzgruppen*—killing squads that followed the German army through Poland, the Baltic, and the Soviet Union—and was well informed about their activities.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] By summer 1942, Auschwitz concentration camp was expanded to accommodate large numbers of deportees for murder or enslavement.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Scores of other concentration camps and satellite camps were set up throughout Europe, with several camps devoted exclusively to extermination.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The victims were killed in concentration and extermination camps and in ghettos, and through mass shootings.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Many victims of the Holocaust were murdered in gas chambers or shot, while others died of starvation or disease or while working as slave labourers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition to eliminating Jews, the Nazis planned to reduce the population of the conquered territories by 30 million people through starvation in an action called the Hunger Plan.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Food supplies would be diverted to the German army and German civilians.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Cities would be razed, and the land allowed to return to forest or resettled by German colonists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Together, the Hunger Plan and *Generalplan Ost* would have led to the starvation of 80 million people in the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] These partially fulfilled plans resulted in additional deaths, bringing the total number of civilians and prisoners of war who died in the democide to an estimated 19.3 million people.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies resulted in the killing of nearly two million non-Jewish Polish civilians, over three million Soviet prisoners of war, communists and other political opponents, homosexuals, the physically and mentally disabled, Jehovah's Witnesses, Adventists, and trade unionists.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler never spoke publicly about the killings and seems to have never visited the concentration camps.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The Nazis embraced the concept of racial hygiene.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 September 1935, Hitler presented two laws—known as the Nuremberg Laws—to the Reichstag.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws banned sexual relations and marriages between Aryans and Jews and were later extended to include "Gypsies, Negroes or their bastard offspring".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws stripped all non-Aryans of their German citizenship and forbade the employment of non-Jewish women under the age of 45 in Jewish households.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's early eugenic policies targeted children with physical and developmental disabilities in a programme dubbed Action Brandt, and he later authorised a euthanasia programme for adults with serious mental and physical disabilities, now referred to as *Aktion T4*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ruled the Nazi Party autocratically by asserting the *Führerprinzip* (leader principle).
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The principle relied on absolute obedience of all subordinates to their superiors; thus, he viewed the government structure as a pyramid, with himself—the infallible leader—at the apex.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Rank in the party was not determined by elections—positions were filled through appointment by those of higher rank, who demanded unquestioning obedience to the will of the leader.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership style was to give contradictory orders to his subordinates and to place them into positions where their duties and responsibilities overlapped with those of others, to have "the stronger one [do] the job".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In this way, Hitler fostered distrust, competition, and infighting among his subordinates to consolidate and maximise his own power.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] His cabinet never met after 1938, and he discouraged his ministers from meeting independently.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler typically did not give written orders; instead, he communicated verbally, or had them conveyed through his close associate Martin Bormann.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He entrusted Bormann with his paperwork, appointments, and personal finances; Bormann used his position to control the flow of information and access to Hitler.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler dominated his country's war effort during World War II to a greater extent than any other national leader.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He strengthened his control of the armed forces in 1938, and subsequently made all major decisions regarding Germany's military strategy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] His decision to mount a risky series of offensives against Norway, France, and the Low Countries in 1940, against the advice of the military, proved successful, though the diplomatic and military strategies he employed in attempts to force the United Kingdom out of the war ended in failure.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler deepened his involvement in the war effort by appointing himself commander-in-chief of the Army in December 1941; from this point forward, he personally directed the war against the Soviet Union, while his military commanders facing the Western Allies retained a degree of autonomy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership became increasingly disconnected from reality as the war turned against Germany, with the military's defensive strategies often hindered by his slow decision-making and frequent directives to hold untenable positions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Nevertheless, he continued to believe that only his leadership could deliver victory.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In the final months of the war, Hitler refused to consider peace negotiations, regarding the destruction of Germany as preferable to surrender.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The military did not challenge Hitler's dominance of the war effort, and senior officers generally supported and enacted his decisions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler created a public image as a celibate man without a domestic life, dedicated entirely to his political mission and the nation.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He met his lover, Eva Braun, in 1929, and married her on 29 April 1945, one day before they both committed suicide.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In September 1931, his half-niece, Geli Raubal, committed suicide with Hitler's gun in his Munich apartment.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] It was rumoured among contemporaries that Geli was in a romantic relationship with him, and her death was a source of deep, lasting pain.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Paula Hitler, the younger sister of Hitler and the last living member of his immediate family, died in June 1960.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was born to a practising Catholic mother and an anti-clerical father; after leaving home, Hitler never again attended Mass or received the sacraments.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Albert Speer stated that Hitler railed against the church to his political associates, and though he never officially left the church, he had no attachment to it.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer added that Hitler felt that in the absence of organised religion, people would turn to mysticism, which he considered regressive.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Speer, Hitler believed that Japanese religious beliefs or Islam would have been a more suitable religion for Germans than Christianity, with its "meekness and flabbiness".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Conway states that Hitler was fundamentally opposed to the Christian churches.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler did not believe in God, was anticlerical, and held Christian ethics in contempt because they contravened his preferred view of "survival of the fittest".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He favoured aspects of Protestantism that suited his own views, and adopted some elements of the Catholic Church's hierarchical organisation, liturgy, and phraseology.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In a 1932 speech, Hitler stated that he was not a Catholic, and declared himself a German Christian.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler viewed the church as an important politically conservative influence on society, and he adopted a strategic relationship with it that "suited his immediate political purposes".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In public, Hitler often praised Christian heritage and German Christian culture, though professing a belief in an "Aryan Jesus" who fought against the Jews.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] However, in *Hitler’s Table Talk* he was recorded as saying Christianity was an "absurdity" and nonsense founded on lies.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] According to a US Office of Strategic Services (OSS) report, "The Nazi Master Plan", Hitler planned to destroy the influence of Christian churches within the Reich.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Shirer commented that "the Nazi regime intended to destroy Christianity in Germany, if it could, and substitute the old paganism of the early tribal Germanic gods with the new paganism of the Nazi extremists".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler wanted to wait until after the war before executing this plan.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Richard Steigmann-Gall has concluded there was no firm evidence of such a plan to replace Christianity.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Swedish historian Mikael Nilsson notes that many of Hitler's religious statements are sourced from *Table Talk*, which he considers highly unreliable: much of the content was written days after the event and was heavily modified to suit the agendas of Martin Bormann and later François Genoud.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer wrote that Hitler had a negative view of Himmler's and Alfred Rosenberg's mystical notions and Himmler's attempt to mythologise the SS.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was more pragmatic, and his ambitions centred on more practical concerns.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Researchers have variously suggested that Hitler suffered from irritable bowel syndrome, skin lesions, irregular heartbeat, coronary sclerosis, Parkinson's disease, syphilis, giant-cell arteritis, tinnitus, and monorchism.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In a report prepared for the OSS in 1943, Walter Charles Langer of Harvard University described Hitler as a "neurotic psychopath" and speculated that he exhibited masochistic tendencies and deep feelings of self-loathing, which he projected onto others, particularly Jews.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In his 1977 book *The Psychopathic God: Adolf Hitler*, the historian Robert G.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Waite proposes that Hitler suffered from borderline personality disorder.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The historians Henrik Eberle and Hans-Joachim Neumann consider that while he suffered from several illnesses, including Parkinson's disease, Hitler did not experience pathological delusions and was always fully aware of, and therefore responsible for, his decisions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Sometime in the 1930s, Hitler adopted a mainly vegetarian diet, avoiding all meat and fish from 1942 onwards.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] At social events, he sometimes gave graphic accounts of the slaughter of animals in an effort to make his guests shun meat.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Bormann had a greenhouse constructed near the Berghof (near Berchtesgaden) to ensure a steady supply of fresh fruit and vegetables for Hitler.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler stopped drinking alcohol around the time he became vegetarian and thereafter only very occasionally drank beer or wine on social occasions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He was a non-smoker for most of his adult life, but smoked heavily in his youth (25 to 40 cigarettes a day); he eventually quit, calling the habit "a waste of money".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He encouraged his close associates to quit by offering a gold watch to anyone able to break the habit.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler began using amphetamine occasionally after 1937 and became addicted to it in late 1942.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer linked this use of amphetamine to Hitler's increasingly erratic behaviour and inflexible decision-making (for example, rarely allowing military retreats).
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Prescribed 90 medications during the war years by his personal physician, Theodor Morell, Hitler took many pills each day for chronic stomach problems and other ailments.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He regularly consumed amphetamine, barbiturates, opiates, and cocaine, as well as potassium bromide and atropa belladonna (the latter in the form of Doktor Koster's Antigaspills).
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He suffered ruptured eardrums as a result of the 20 July plot bomb blast in 1944, and 200 wood splinters had to be removed from his legs.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Newsreel footage of Hitler shows tremors in his left hand and a shuffling walk, which began before the war and worsened towards the end of his life.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Ernst-Günther Schenck and several other doctors who met Hitler in the last weeks of his life also formed a diagnosis of Parkinson's disease.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian Joachim Fest, Hitler's suicide was likened by numerous contemporaries to a "spell" being broken.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian John Toland, Nazism "burst like a bubble" without its leader.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw describes Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] "Never in history has such ruination—physical and moral—been associated with the name of one man", he adds.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's political programme brought about a world war, leaving behind a devastated and impoverished Eastern and Central Europe.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany suffered wholesale destruction, characterised as *Stunde Null* (Zero Hour).
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies inflicted human suffering on an unprecedented scale; according to R.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Rummel, the Nazi regime was responsible for the democidal killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre of World War II.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The number of civilians killed during the Second World War was unprecedented in the history of warfare.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians, philosophers, and politicians often use the word "evil" to describe the Nazi regime.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Many European countries have criminalised both the promotion of Nazism and Holocaust denial.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Friedrich Meinecke described Hitler as "one of the great examples of the singular and incalculable power of personality in historical life".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The English historian Hugh Trevor-Roper saw him as "among the 'terrible simplifiers' of history, the most systematic, the most historical, the most philosophical, and yet the coarsest, cruelest, least magnanimous conqueror the world has ever known".
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Roberts, Hitler's defeat marked the end of a phase of European history dominated by Germany.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] In its place emerged the Cold War, a global confrontation between the Western Bloc, dominated by the United States and other NATO nations, and the Eastern Bloc, dominated by the Soviet Union.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Sebastian Haffner asserted that without Hitler and the displacement of the Jews, the modern nation-state of Israel would not exist.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He contends that without Hitler, the de-colonisation of former European spheres of influence would have been postponed.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Further, Haffner claimed that other than Alexander the Great, Hitler had a more significant impact than any other comparable historical figure, in that he too caused a wide range of worldwide changes in a relatively short time span.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler exploited documentary films and newsreels to inspire a cult of personality.
[src:alexander-kerensky/adolf-hitler-p02] He was involved and appeared in a series of propaganda films throughout his political career, many made by Leni Riefenstahl, regarded as a pioneer of modern filmmaking.
[src:alexander-kerensky/aleksandr-khvostov] He served as Minister of Justice from July 19, 1915, to July 22, 1916, and was responsible for the trial of Vladimir Sukhomlinov.
[src:alexander-kerensky/aleksandr-khvostov] He became Minister of Interior from July 22, 1916, to September 29, 1916 (New Style).
[src:alexander-kerensky/aleksandr-khvostov] He was (and became known as) the uncle of Alexei Khvostov.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] After the February Revolution of 1917, he joined the newly formed provisional government, first as Minister of Justice, then as Minister of War, and after July as the government's second Minister-Chairman.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He was the leader of the social-democratic Trudovik faction of the Socialist Revolutionary Party.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was also a vice-chairman of the Petrograd Soviet, a position that held a sizable amount of power.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky became the prime minister of the Provisional Government, and his tenure was consumed with World War I.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Despite mass opposition to the war, Kerensky chose to continue Russia's participation.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] His government cracked down on anti-war sentiment and dissent in 1917, which made his administration even more unpopular.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky remained in power until the October Revolution.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] This revolution saw the Bolsheviks create a government led by them in a coalition with the Left Socialist-Revolutionaries, to replace Kerensky's government.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky fled Russia and lived the remainder of his life in exile, mostly in Paris and New York City.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He also worked for the Hoover Institution at Stanford University, California.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He died in New York on 11 June 1970, at the age of 89.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Both the local Russian and Serbian Orthodox churches refused his body due to his Freemasonry, and because they saw him as largely responsible for the Bolshevik seizure of power.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Eventually, his body was flown to London and buried in the non-sectarian Putney Vale Cemetery.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Alexander Kerensky was born in Simbirsk (now Ulyanovsk) on the Volga river on 4 May 1881 and was the eldest son in the family.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] His father, Fyodor Mikhailovich Kerensky, was a teacher and director of the local gymnasium, and was later promoted to be an inspector of public schools.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] His paternal grandfather Mikhail Ivanovich served as a priest in the village of Kerenka in the Gorodishchensky district of the Penza Governorate from 1830.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The surname Kerensky comes from the name of this village.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] His maternal grandfather was head of the Topographical Bureau of the Kazan Military District.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] His mother, Nadezhda Aleksandrovna (née Adler), was the granddaughter of a former serf who had managed to purchase his freedom before serfdom was abolished in 1861.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He subsequently embarked upon a mercantile career, in which he prospered.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] This allowed him to move his business to Moscow, where he continued his success and became a wealthy Moscow merchant.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Members of the Kerensky and Ulyanov families were friends; Kerensky's father was the teacher of Vladimir Ulyanov (Lenin), and had even secured him acceptance into the University of Kazan.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] In 1889, when Kerensky was eight, the family moved to Tashkent, where his father had been appointed the superintendent of public schools.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky graduated with honours in 1899.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Petersburg University, where he studied history and philology.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He earned his law degree in 1904 and married Olga Lvovna Baranovskaya, the daughter of a Russian general, the same year.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky joined the Narodnik movement and worked as a legal counsel to victims of the Revolution of 1905.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] At the end of 1904, he was jailed on suspicion of belonging to a militant group.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Afterwards, he gained a reputation for his work as a defence lawyer in a number of political trials of revolutionaries.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] In 1912, Kerensky became widely known when he visited the goldfields at the Lena River and published material about the Lena massacre.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] In fact, the Socialist Revolutionary Party bought Kerensky a house, as he otherwise would not be eligible for election to the Duma, according to the Russian property laws.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] 8. stop the harassment of legal trade union organizations.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] In August, he became a significant member of the Progressive Bloc, which included several socialist parties, Mensheviks, and Liberals – but not Bolsheviks.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was an active member of the irregular Freemasonic lodge the Grand Orient of Russia's Peoples, which derived from the Grand Orient of France.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was Secretary-General of the Grand Orient of Russia's Peoples and stood down following his ascent to the government in July 1917.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He was succeeded by a Menshevik, Alexander Halpern.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] According to Kerensky, Rasputin had terrorised the empress by threatening to return to his native village.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Members of the nobility murdered Rasputin in December 1916, and he was buried near the imperial residence in Tsarskoye Selo.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Shortly after the February Revolution of 1917, Kerensky ordered soldiers to re-bury the corpse at an unmarked spot in the countryside.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] However, the truck broke down or was forced to stop because of the snow on Lesnoe Road outside of St.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] It is likely the corpse was incinerated (between 3 and 7 in the morning) in the cauldrons of the nearby boiler shop of the Saint Petersburg State Polytechnical University, including the coffin, without leaving a single trace.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] When the February Revolution broke out in 1917, Kerensky – together with Pavel Milyukov – was one of its most prominent leaders.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] As one of the Duma's most well-known speakers against the monarchy and as a lawyer and defender of many revolutionaries, Kerensky became a member of the Provisional Committee of the State Duma and was elected vice-chairman of the newly formed Petrograd Soviet.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] These two bodies, the Duma and the Petrograd Soviet, or – rather – their respective executive committees, soon became each other's antagonists on most matters except regarding the end of the tsar's autocracy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The Petrograd Soviet grew to include 3000 to 4000 members, and their meetings could drown into a blur of lengthy speeches.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] 28 February] 1917 the executive committee of the Petrograd Soviet, or Ispolkom, formed a self-appointed committee, with (eventually) three members from each of the parties represented in the Soviet.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky became one of the members representing the Socialist Revolutionary Party (the SRs).
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] 1 March] 1917, without any consultation with the government, the Ispolkom of the Soviet issued the infamous Order No.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] 1, intended only for the 160,000-strong Petrograd garrison, but soon interpreted as applicable to all soldiers at the front.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The order stipulated that all military units should form committees like the Petrograd Soviet.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] This led to confusion and "stripping of officers' authority"; further, "Order No.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] 3" stipulated that the military was subordinate to Ispolkom in the political hierarchy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The ideas came from a group of socialists and aimed to limit the officers' power to military affairs.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The socialist intellectuals believed the officers to be the most likely counterrevolutionary elements.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's role in these orders is unclear, but he participated in the decisions.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] But just as before the revolution he had defended many who disliked the tsar, he now saved the lives of many of the tsar's civil servants about to be lynched by mobs.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Additionally, the Duma formed an executive committee which eventually became the Russian Provisional Government.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] As there was little trust between Ispolkom and this government (and as he was about to accept the office of Attorney General in the Provisional Government), Kerensky gave a most passionate speech, not just to the Ispolkom, but to the entire Petrograd Soviet.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He then swore, as minister, never to violate democratic values, and ended his speech with the words "I cannot live without the people.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] In the moment you begin to doubt me, then kill me." The huge majority (workers and soldiers) gave him great applause, and Kerensky now became the first and *the only one* who participated in both the Provisional Government and the Ispolkom.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] As a link between Ispolkom and the Provisional Government, Kerensky stood to benefit from this position.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] After the first government crisis over Milyukov's secret note re-committing Russia to its original war-aims on 2–4 May, Kerensky became the Minister of War and the dominant figure in the newly formed socialist-liberal coalition government.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] On 10 May (Julian calendar), Kerensky started for the front and visited one division after another, urging the men to do their duty.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] His speeches were impressive and convincing for the moment, but had little lasting effect.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Under Allied pressure to continue the war, he launched what became known as the Kerensky Offensive against the Austro-Hungarian/German South Army on 1 July [O.S.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] At first successful, the offensive soon met strong resistance and the Central Powers riposted with a strong counter-attack.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The Russian army retreated and suffered heavy losses, and it became clear from many incidents of desertion, sabotage, and mutiny that the army was no longer willing to attack.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Many officers scornfully referred to commander-in-chief Kerensky as the "persuader-in-chief".
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] On 2 July 1917 the Provisional Government's first coalition collapsed over the question of Ukraine's autonomy.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Following the July Days unrest in Petrograd (3–7 July [16–20 July, N.S.] 1917) and the official suppression of the Bolsheviks, Kerensky succeeded Lvov as Russia's prime minister on 21 July [O.S.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Following the Kornilov Affair, an attempted military coup d'état at the end of August, and the resignation of the other ministers, he appointed himself Supreme Commander-in-Chief, as well.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He formed a five-member Directory, which consisted of himself, Minister of Foreign Affairs Mikhail Tereshchenko, Minister of War General Aleksandr Verkhovsky, Minister of the Navy Admiral Dmitry Verderevsky and Minister of Posts and Telegraphs Aleksei Nikitin.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He retained his post in the final coalition government in October 1917 until the Bolsheviks overthrew it on 7 November [O.S.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky faced a major challenge: three years of participation in World War had exhausted Russia, while the provisional government offered little motivation for a victory outside of continuing Russia's obligations towards its allies.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Russia's continued involvement in the war was not popular among the lower and middle classes, and especially not popular among the soldiers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] They had all believed that Russia would stop fighting when the Provisional Government took power, and subsequently felt deceived.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Furthermore, Lenin and his Bolshevik party were promising "peace, land, and bread" under a communist system.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The Russian army, war-weary, ill-equipped, dispirited and ill-disciplined, was disintegrating, with soldiers deserting in large numbers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] By autumn 1917, an estimated two million men had unofficially left the army.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The dilemma of whether to withdraw was a great one, and Kerensky's inconsistent and impractical policies further destabilised the army and the country at large.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Furthermore, Kerensky adopted a policy that isolated the right-wing conservatives and nationalists, both democratic and monarchist-oriented.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] His philosophy of "no enemies to the left" greatly empowered the Bolsheviks and gave them a free hand, allowing them to take over the military arm or "voyenka" (Russian: Военка) of the Petrograd and Moscow Soviets.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] During the Kornilov Affair, Kerensky had distributed arms to the Petrograd workers, and by November most of these armed workers had gone over to the Bolsheviks.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] 25–26 October] 1917, the Bolsheviks launched the second Russian revolution of the year.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's government in Petrograd had almost no support in the city.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The Bolsheviks overthrew the government rapidly by seizing governmental buildings and the Winter Palace.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky escaped the Bolsheviks and fled to Pskov, where he rallied some loyal troops for an attempt to re-take the city.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] His troops managed to capture Tsarskoye Selo but were beaten the next day at Pulkovo.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky narrowly escaped, and he spent the next few weeks in hiding before fleeing the country, eventually arriving in France.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] During the Russian Civil War, he supported neither side, as he opposed both the Bolshevik regime and the White Movement.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Meanwhile, viewed by Woodrow Wilson as the spokesman for Russian democracy, he strongly influenced Wilson on Russian matters.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky was married to Olga Lvovna Baranovskaya and they had two sons, Oleg (1905–1984) and Gleb (1907–1990), who both went on to become engineers.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's grandson (also named Oleg), according to the Internet Movie Database, played his grandfather's role in the 1981 film *Reds*.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky and Olga were divorced in 1939 soon after he settled in Paris, and in the same year, while visiting the United States, he met and secretly married Lydia Ellen "Nell" Tritton (1899–1946), the Australian former journalist who had become his press secretary and translator.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The marriage took place in Martins Creek, Pennsylvania.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] When Germany invaded France in 1940, they emigrated to the United States.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] During the Nazi invasion of the Soviet Union, Kerensky expressed his willingness to support the Russian people's defense against Hitler, despite his long-standing opposition to the Soviet regime.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] In a published article, he criticized both Lenin and Stalin but stated that the survival of Russia as a nation took precedence over political differences.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] When his wife Nell became terminally ill in 1945, Kerensky travelled with her to Brisbane, Australia, and lived there with her family.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] She suffered a stroke in February 1946, and he remained there until her death on 10 April 1946.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky then returned to the United States, where he spent the rest of his life.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He wrote and broadcast extensively on Russian politics and history.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] His last public lecture was delivered at Kalamazoo College in Kalamazoo, Michigan, in October 1967.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky died of arteriosclerotic heart disease at St.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Luke's Hospital in New York City on 11 June 1970 at the age of 89, after being initially admitted for injuries sustained from a fall.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] He was one of the last surviving major participants in the turbulent events of 1917.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] The local Russian Orthodox Churches in New York City refused to grant Kerensky burial rites because of his association with Freemasonry, and because they saw him as largely responsible for the Bolsheviks' seizure of power.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] A Serbian Orthodox Church also refused burial rites.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Kerensky's body was flown to London, where his two sons resided; he was buried at the non-denominational Putney Vale Cemetery.
[src:alexander-kerensky/alexander-kerensky] Papers of the Kerensky family are held at the Cadbury Research Library, University of Birmingham.
